A

[absolute zero](/Absolute_zero)
A purely theoretical state, a conceptual abyss concerning a [physical system](/Physical_system) at the absolute lowest boundary of the [thermodynamic temperature](/Thermodynamic_temperature) scale. This is the fabled zero [kelvins](/Kelvin) (0 K), a point where, in theory, the system neither emits nor absorbs any [energy](/Energy)—implying that all constituent [atoms](/Atom) are, quite literally, at rest. It's a state of minimum possible [enthalpy](/Enthalpy) and maximum [order](/Order_(physics)). Through the rather elegant, albeit somewhat idealized, extrapolation of the [ideal gas law](/Ideal_gas_law), the internationally sanctioned value for this elusive state has been precisely determined as −273.15&#160;°C (−459.67&#160;°F; 0.00&#160;K). Achieving this in practice is, predictably, impossible, but scientists continue to get tantalizingly close, pushing the boundaries of the [Third Law of Thermodynamics](/Laws_of_thermodynamics).

[absorbance](/Absorbance)
A quantitative measure, typically dimensionless, of the extent to which a sample absorbs [light](/Light) (or any other form of [electromagnetic radiation](/Electromagnetic_radiation)) at a specific wavelength. It's derived from the ratio of the incident radiation to the transmitted radiation through the sample. High absorbance means less light gets through; rather intuitive, wouldn't you say? This concept is foundational in [spectroscopy](/Spectroscopy) and the [Beer–Lambert law](/Beer%E2%80%93Lambert_law), allowing for the determination of [concentration](/Concentration) of a [solute](/Solute) in a [solution](/Solution_(chemistry)).

[absorption](/Absorption_(chemistry))
1.&#160;&#160;This refers to the intrinsic [physical](/Physical_process) or [chemical process](/Chemical_process) whereby a substance, initially in one [state of matter](/State_of_matter), becomes thoroughly integrated into and subsequently retained by another substance residing in a *different* state. The key distinction here, often lost on the less discerning, is that absorption involves the first substance permeating the *entire bulk* of the second, rather than merely clinging to its surface. This is a crucial difference from [adsorption](/Adsorption), which is a superficial affair.
2.&#160;&#160;More specifically, in the realm of [electromagnetic radiation](/Electromagnetic_radiation), this is the [process](/Absorption_(electromagnetic_radiation)) through which [matter](/Matter) (typically the [electrons](/Electron) bound within [atoms](/Atom)) captures the [energy](/Energy) from such radiation. This absorbed energy is then transformed into various forms of internal energy, most commonly manifesting as [thermal energy](/Thermal_energy). This particular phenomenon of absorption forms the fundamental principle upon which [spectrophotometry](/Spectrophotometry) is based, allowing us to quantify substances by their unique light-absorbing characteristics.

[abundance](/Abundance_(chemistry))
A measure of how prevalent a particular [chemical element](/Chemical_element) or [chemical species](/Chemical_species) is within a given [sample](/Sample_(material)), [environment](/Environment), or even the entire [universe](/Universe). It can be expressed in various ways: as a [mass fraction](/Mass_fraction_(chemistry)), [mole fraction](/Molar_fraction), or [number density](/Number_density). For instance, the [natural abundance](/Natural_abundance) of [isotopes](/Isotope) is a critical factor in understanding the average [atomic mass](/Atomic_mass) of an element.

[accuracy](/Accuracy)
A rather vital, yet frequently elusive, concept in measurement. It quantifies how near a measured value actually is to the *actual* or *true* value of the quantity being observed. One might think this is obvious, but apparently, it needs stating. Do not, under any circumstances, confuse it with [precision](/Precision), which, while important, is an entirely different beast.

[acetyl](/Acetyl)
A [functional group](/Functional_group) in [organic chemistry](/Organic_chemistry), specifically an acyl group, with the formula –COCH3. It's a carbonyl group (C=O) bonded to a methyl group. Often found in important biological and synthetic compounds, like [acetylcholine](/Acetylcholine) or [acetylsalicylic acid](/Aspirin) (aspirin, for the uninitiated).

[achiral](/Achiral)
(Of a [molecule](/Molecule)) Possessing a geometric symmetry that renders it utterly indistinguishable from its own [mirror image](/Mirror_image). Essentially, it lacks the property of [chirality](/Chirality_(chemistry)), meaning it can be perfectly superimposed onto its reflection. Think of a common spoon; it's achiral. Your left hand, however, is decidedly chiral.

[acid](/Acid)
Ah, [acids](/Acid), the bane of many a first-year student. They come in flavors, each adding a layer of... *nuance* to the definition.
1.&#160;&#160;([Brønsted–Lowry acid](/Br%C3%B8nsted%E2%80%93Lowry_acid%E2%80%93base_theory)) Any [chemical species](/Chemical_species) or [molecular entity](/Molecular_entity) that performs the rather generous act of donating a [proton](/Proton) (H+
) when it engages in a [reaction](/Chemical_reaction) with another species. This other species, by definition, is a [Brønsted–Lowry base](/Br%C3%B8nsted%E2%80%93Lowry_acid%E2%80%93base_theory). If you dissolve such a proton donor in an [aqueous solution](/Aqueous_solution), and it consequently elevates the [concentration](/Concentration) of [hydronium ion](/Hydronium) (H
3 O+
) by transferring protons to [water](/Water_(molecule)) molecules, then you may also, rather redundantly, call it an [Arrhenius acid](/Arrhenius_acid). When the term "acid" is tossed around without further qualification, it's typically this Brønsted–Lowry iteration that's implicitly being discussed. You're welcome for the clarification. [1]
2.&#160;&#160;([Lewis acid](/Lewis_acid)) A more expansive, and some might say, *elegant*, definition. This refers to any [chemical species](/Chemical_species) or [molecular entity](/Molecular_entity) that acts as an *[electron pair](/Electron_pair) acceptor* during a reaction with another species. It forms a [covalent bond](/Covalent_bond) by graciously accepting a [lone pair of electrons](/Lone_pair) donated by the other species, which is, naturally, a [Lewis base](/Lewis_base). This definition was intended to generalize the Brønsted–Lowry concept, proposing that [acid–base reactions](/Acid%E2%80%93base_reaction) are more accurately viewed as reorganizations of electrons rather than mere proton transfers. The Lewis acid either directly accepts electron pairs or achieves this indirectly by releasing protons (H+
) into a solution, which then perform the electron-pair acceptance. This definition is inclusive of many Brønsted–Lowry acids, though, annoyingly, not all. And, to add to the confusion, most Lewis acids are *not* Brønsted–Lowry acids, and vice versa. It's almost as if the universe enjoys complexity for its own sake. [1]
3.&#160;&#160;Colloquially, and with a distinct lack of precision, "acid" refers to any compound that, when dissolved in water, produces a [pH](/PH) value below 7.0. This common usage often refers to the entire aqueous solution, whereas the stricter definitions above are concerned solely with the acidic [solute](/Solute) itself. One can only sigh at such imprecision. [2]

[acid anhydride](/Acid_anhydride)
Any [chemical compound](/Chemical_compound) that is conceptually, or actually, derived by the removal of [water molecules](/Water_(molecule)) from an [acid](/Acid). It's essentially the dehydrated form of an acid. The inverse, naturally, is a [base anhydride](/Base_anhydride).

[acid dissociation constant](/Acid_dissociation_constant) (K a)
Also known as the *acid ionization constant* or *acidity constant*. A rather crucial [quantitative measure](/Quantitative_property) of an [acid's](/Acid) inherent [strength](/Acid_strength) when it's in a [solution](/Solution_(chemistry)). It is articulated as an [equilibrium constant](/Equilibrium_constant) for the [chemical dissociation reaction](/Dissociation_(chemistry)) within the context of [acid–base reactions](/Acid%E2%80%93base_reaction). Frequently, to make things more manageable, it's expressed as its base-10 cologarithm, which we affectionately call [pKa](/PKa). A low pKa indicates a strong acid.

[acid–base extraction](/Acid%E2%80%93base_extraction)
A [chemical reaction](/Chemical_reaction) or, more accurately, a [separation process](/Separation_process), where specific [chemical species](/Chemical_species) are selectively isolated from other [acids](/Acid) and [bases](/Base_(chemistry)) within a mixture, typically by manipulating their [solubility](/Solubility) based on [pH](/PH) changes. It's a common technique in [organic chemistry](/Organic_chemistry) for purifying compounds.

[acid–base reaction](/Acid%E2%80%93base_reaction)
A [chemical reaction](/Chemical_reaction) that involves the exchange of [protons](/Proton) (H+
) or [electron pairs](/Electron_pair) between reacting [species](/Chemical_species), as defined by [Brønsted–Lowry](/Br%C3%B8nsted%E2%80%93Lowry_acid%E2%80%93base_theory) or [Lewis theories](/Lewis_acid_and_base), respectively. These reactions are fundamental to countless chemical and biological processes, leading to the formation of [salts](/Salt_(chemistry)) and [water](/Water_(molecule)) in many cases.

[acidic](/Acidic)
The characteristic property of a [substance](/Chemical_substance) or [solution](/Solution_(chemistry)) that exhibits the traits of an [acid](/Acid). This typically means a [pH](/PH) of less than 7 in [aqueous solutions](/Aqueous_solution), a propensity to donate [protons](/Proton), or an ability to accept [electron pairs](/Electron_pair). It's not exactly rocket science.

[actinides](/Actinoid)
Also known, somewhat redundantly, as *actinoids*. This is the periodic series of [metallic elements](/Metal) with [atomic numbers](/Atomic_number) ranging from 89 to 103. This includes everything from [actinium](/Actinium) (Ac) all the way through to [lawrencium](/Lawrencium) (Lr). They are all [radioactive](/Radioactive_decay) and often quite unstable, a rather inconvenient family of elements.

[activated complex](/Activated_complex)
A transient, high-energy, and highly unstable molecular structure that forms instantaneously at the peak of the [activation energy](/Activation_energy) barrier during a [chemical reaction](/Chemical_reaction). It's the fleeting moment of molecular rearrangement as old [bonds](/Chemical_bond) break and new ones begin to form due to a collision between reactant [molecules](/Molecule). It exists for such a brief period that it cannot be isolated.

[activation energy](/Activation_energy)
The absolute minimum [energy](/Energy) that *must* be available to a [chemical system](/Physical_system) containing potential [reactants](/Reactant) in order for a specific [chemical reaction](/Chemical_reaction) to actually occur. Think of it as the initial push required to get the ball rolling; without it, the reaction simply won't proceed, regardless of how thermodynamically favorable it might be. This barrier is what the [activated complex](/Activated_complex) must overcome.

activity series
See [reactivity series](/Reactivity_series). Because sometimes, even chemists can't commit to a single name.

[actual yield](/Actual_yield)
The quantity of product that is *actually* obtained from a [chemical reaction](/Chemical_reaction) in a laboratory or industrial setting. This is almost invariably less than the [theoretical yield](/Yield_(chemistry)) due to various inefficiencies, side reactions, and the inherent messiness of reality.

[acyclic](/Open-chain_compound)
(Of a [molecule](/Molecule)) Characterized by containing only linear, or non-ring, arrangements of [atoms](/Atom). This term is particularly relevant in the context of [hydrocarbons](/Hydrocarbon), distinguishing them from their [cyclic](/Cyclic_compound) counterparts.

[addition reaction](/Addition_reaction)
In the grand theater of [organic chemistry](/Organic_chemistry), this is a type of [chemical reaction](/Chemical_reaction) where two or more [molecules](/Molecule) decide to combine, rather amicably, to form a single, larger molecule. Typically, this involves the breaking of a [pi bond](/Pi_bond) (like a [double bond](/Double_bond) or [triple bond](/Triple_bond)) and the formation of new [sigma bonds](/Sigma_bond).

[adduct](/Adduct)
A distinct [chemical species](/Chemical_species) that emerges as the *sole* product from an [addition reaction](/Addition_reaction) between two other distinct reactant species. The defining characteristic is that *all* the [atoms](/Atom) that originally constituted the reactants are retained within this single product. Connectivity might change, certainly, but no atoms are lost, nor are any magically gained that weren't present in the initial reactant molecules. [Stoichiometries](/Stoichiometry) other than 1:1 are, predictably, also possible—for example, a bis-adduct (2:1). [2]

[adhesion](/Adhesion)
The intrinsic propensity of dissimilar [particles](/Particle) or [surfaces](/Surface_science) to cling to one another. This phenomenon is a direct consequence of various [intermolecular forces](/Intermolecular_force) acting between the different substances. It is, quite distinctly, the opposite of [cohesion](/Cohesion_(chemistry)), where similar particles stick together.

[adsorption](/Adsorption)
A [chemical adhesion](/Adhesion) where [atoms](/Atom), [ions](/Ion), or [molecules](/Molecule) of one substance (be it a [gas](/Gas), [liquid](/Liquid), or [dissolved solid](/Solid)) attach themselves *exclusively* to the surface of another substance. This results in a thin film of the first substance being somewhat weakly bonded to the [interface](/Interface_(matter)) between the two. Crucially, adsorption is a *surface phenomenon*, contrasting sharply with [absorption](/Absorption_(chemistry)), which involves the full bulk of the material. Pay attention, the distinction is important.

[aeration](/Aeration)
The process of introducing [air](/Air) (or, more generally, a [gas](/Gas)) into a [liquid](/Liquid) or a [solid](/Solid). This is often done to promote [oxidation](/Oxidation) reactions, remove volatile compounds, or simply to ensure uniform mixing.

[alcohol](/Alcohol_(chemistry))
Any [organic compound](/Organic_compound) defined by the presence of at least one [hydroxyl group](/Hydroxy_group) (–OH) unequivocally attached to a [saturated carbon atom](/Saturated_hydrocarbon). Alcohols follow the general formula R–OH, where 'R' represents an [alkyl](/Alkyl_group) or [aryl](/Aryl) group. They are versatile compounds, serving as [solvents](/Solvent), [fuels](/Fuel), and [intermediates](/Reactive_intermediate) in countless syntheses.

[aldehyde](/Aldehyde)
Both a [functional group](/Functional_group) and a class of [organic compounds](/Organic_compound). It consists of a [carbonyl group](/Carbonyl) (C=O) double-bonded to a [hydrogen atom](/Hydrogen) and also bonded to any other 'R'-group (which is typically a carbon-containing [substituent](/Substituent)). Aldehydes are characterized by the general formula R–C(H)=O. They are highly reactive and are crucial in [organic synthesis](/Chemical_synthesis).

The skeletal formula for a generic [aldehyde](/Aldehyde), where R denotes a variable carbon-containing [substituent group](/Substituent).
[aliphatic](/Aliphatic)
(Of an [organic compound](/Organic_compound)) Characterized by an [open-chain](/Open-chain_compound) structure of [carbon atoms](/Carbon), as opposed to [aromatic](/Aromatic_compound) rings. This includes [alkanes](/Alkane), [alkenes](/Alkene), and [alkynes](/Alkyne). It’s the simpler, less aesthetically pleasing side of organic structures, devoid of fancy rings.

[alkali metal](/Alkali_metal)
Any of the highly [reactive metallic elements](/Metal) that proudly reside in Group 1 of the [periodic table](/Periodic_table_of_the_elements). This esteemed group includes [lithium](/Lithium) (Li), [sodium](/Sodium) (Na), [potassium](/Potassium) (K), [rubidium](/Rubidium) (Rb), [caesium](/Caesium) (Cs), and the notoriously unstable [francium](/Francium) (Fr). They are characterized by having a single [valence electron](/Valence_electron), which they are all too eager to shed, leading to their vigorous reactions with [water](/Water_(molecule)) and other [non-metals](/Non-metal).

[alkaline](/Alkaline)
Possessing the characteristics of a [base](/Base_(chemistry)). In [aqueous solution](/Aqueous_solution), this translates to a [pH](/PH) greater than 7.0. It's the opposite of [acidic](/Acidic), a concept that should be self-evident.

[alkaline earth metal](/Alkaline_earth_metal)
Any of the [metallic elements](/Metal) found in Group 2 of the [periodic table](/Periodic_table_of_the_elements). This includes [beryllium](/Beryllium) (Be), [magnesium](/Magnesium) (Mg), [calcium](/Calcium) (Ca), [strontium](/Strontium) (Sr), [barium](/Barium) (Ba), and [radium](/Radium) (Ra). They possess two [valence electrons](/Valence_electron) and are less reactive than [alkali metals](/Alkali_metal) but still quite eager to form [ions](/Ion) with a +2 charge.

[alkane](/Alkane)
Also known, less formally, as *paraffin*. This refers to any fully [saturated acyclic hydrocarbon](/Acyclic_compound), meaning it's an [organic compound](/Organic_compound) composed solely of [carbon](/Carbon) and [hydrogen atoms](/Hydrogen) where all carbon–carbon [bonds](/Chemical_bond) are exclusively [single bonds](/Multiple_bond). They are generally unreactive, hence the "paraffin" moniker (from *parum affinis*, "little affinity").

[alkene](/Alkene)
Also known, colloquially, as *olefin*. This is any [unsaturated hydrocarbon](/Unsaturated_hydrocarbon) that contains at least one carbon–carbon [double bond](/Double_bond). The presence of this double bond makes them significantly more reactive than [alkanes](/Alkane), undergoing various [addition reactions](/Addition_reaction).

[alkoxy](/Alkoxy)
A [functional group](/Functional_group) in [organic chemistry](/Organic_chemistry) where an [alkyl group](/Alkyl_group) is bonded to an [oxygen atom](/Oxygen), which is in turn bonded to the rest of the molecule. Its general formula is R–O–, where R is an alkyl group. It's essentially an [ether](/Ether) with only one side specified, a rather incomplete picture for a functional group.

[alkyl](/Alkyl_group)
The [substituent](/Substituent) form of an [alkane](/Alkane)—that is, any alkane that has, rather rudely, had a [hydrogen atom](/Hydrogen) removed, leaving an open [bond](/Chemical_bond) for attachment. This term is broad, encompassing various [functional groups](/Functional_group) like a [methyl](/Methyl), [ethyl](/Ethyl_group), or [propyl group](/Propyl). They are the fundamental building blocks of many [organic compounds](/Organic_compound).

[alkyne](/Alkyne)
Also known, in older nomenclature, as *acetylene*. This is any [unsaturated hydrocarbon](/Unsaturated_hydrocarbon) that contains at least one carbon–carbon [triple bond](/Multiple_bond). Like [alkenes](/Alkene), the triple bond makes them quite reactive, participating in [addition reactions](/Addition_reaction) and having distinct [geometries](/Molecular_geometry).

[allomer](/Allomer)
A rather specific term for a [substance](/Chemical_substance) that, despite possessing a different [chemical composition](/Chemical_composition) (i.e., made of different [elements](/Chemical_element) or in different proportions), curiously exhibits the exact same [crystalline structure](/Crystal_structure) as another substance. It’s an interesting quirk of solid-state arrangement.

[allotrope](/Allotrope)
Any of a diverse range of distinct structural forms that can be adopted by the *same* [chemical element](/Chemical_element). This is not about different compounds, but different physical manifestations of the *pure element*. Carbon, for instance, is a prime example, gracing us with [diamonds](/Diamonds) (a rather ostentatious form), [graphite](/Graphite) (useful for pencils and nuclear reactors), and the more recently discovered [fullerenes](/Fullerene) (those peculiar buckyballs). Each allotrope possesses unique [physical](/Physical_property) and [chemical properties](/Chemical_property).

[alloy](/Alloy)
A [mixture](/Mixture) primarily composed of [metals](/Metal), or a metal combined with one or more other [elements](/Chemical_element), where the combination collectively exhibits a characteristic [metallic bonding](/Metallic_bond) character. These are not mere mixtures but often form [solid solutions](/Solid_solution) or [intermetallic compounds](/Intermetallic). Common examples, which you should already know, include [bronze](/Bronze) (copper and tin), [brass](/Brass) (copper and zinc), and [pewter](/Pewter) (primarily tin). Their properties often surpass those of their individual constituents.

[amalgam](/Amalgam_(chemistry))
A rather specific type of [alloy](/Alloy) where one of the constituent [metals](/Metal) is, rather notably, [mercury](/Mercury_(element)). Historically, dental amalgams were a common application, though their use has seen decline.

[ambident](/Ambident)
(Of a [molecule](/Molecule) or [functional group](/Functional_group)) Possessing two distinct, yet interacting, [reaction sites](/Reaction_site), to either of which a [bond](/Chemical_bond) may be formed during a [chemical reaction](/Chemical_reaction). This dual reactivity leads to interesting, and sometimes unpredictable, synthetic pathways.

[amide](/Amide)
A [functional group](/Functional_group) in [organic chemistry](/Organic_chemistry) containing a [carbonyl group](/Carbonyl) (C=O) linked to a [nitrogen atom](/Nitrogen). The general formula is R–CO–NR′R″. Amides are fundamental in [peptide bonds](/Peptide_bond) that link [amino acids](/Amino_acid) in [proteins](/Protein), making them vital in [biochemistry](/Biochemistry).

[ammoniacal](/Ammoniacal)
Describing a [solution](/Solution_(chemistry)) where the [solvent](/Solvent) is [aqueous ammonia](/Ammonia). This implies the presence of [ammonia](/Ammonia) dissolved in [water](/Water_(molecule)), often creating a [basic](/Basic_(chemistry)) environment. [3]

[amorphous solid](/Amorphous_solid)
A [solid](/Solid) material that lacks the long-range, ordered [crystalline structure](/Crystal_structure) characteristic of true [crystals](/Crystal). Its constituent [atoms](/Atom) or [molecules](/Molecule) are arranged in a more random, disordered fashion, similar to a [liquid](/Liquid), but frozen in place. [Glass](/Glass) is a classic example.

[amount of substance](/Amount_of_substance)
Also known, rather quaintly, as *enplethy*, or more plainly, *chemical amount* or simply *amount*. This is a measure of the number of discrete [particles](/Particle) (such as [molecules](/Molecule), [atoms](/Atom), [ions](/Ion), [electrons](/Electron), or any other atomic-scale entity) present in a given [sample of matter](/Matter). It is fundamentally defined as this number of particles divided by the [Avogadro constant](/Avogadro_constant). The [SI unit](/International_System_of_Units) for amount of substance is the [mole](/Mole_(unit)) (mol), a concept so central to chemistry it's almost insulting to explain.

[amphipathic](/Amphipathic)
(Of a [molecule](/Molecule)) Possessing both [hydrophilic](/Hydrophilic) (water-loving) and [hydrophobic](/Hydrophobic) (water-fearing) groups within its structure. This dual nature allows such molecules to interact with both polar and nonpolar environments, making them crucial for things like [wetting agents](/Wetting_agent) and the formation of [cell membranes](/Cell_membrane) from [membrane lipids](/Membrane_lipid). [4]

[amphoteric](/Amphoteric)
Also known as *amphiprotic*. (Of a [chemical species](/Chemical_species)) Exhibiting the remarkable ability to behave as *both* an [acid](/Acid) and a [base](/Base_(chemistry)), depending entirely on the [medium](/Medium) or [solvent](/Solvent) in which it finds itself. [Water](/Water_(molecule)) itself is a prime example. Another, perhaps less obvious, is [sulfuric acid](/Sulfuric_acid) (H2SO4), which, while a notoriously strong acid in water, can act more like a base in [superacids](/Superacid).

[amyl](/Pentyl)
A common, though non-systematic, name for a [pentyl group](/Pentyl). It's always entertaining how many trivial names persist.

[analyte](/Analyte)
The specific [substance](/Chemical_substance) or [chemical constituent](/Chemical_composition) that is the *object of interest* in a [chemical analysis](/Chemical_analysis). It's what you're trying to identify or quantify, the star of your analytical show.

[analytical chemistry](/Analytical_chemistry)
The branch of [chemistry](/Chemistry) dedicated to the rather meticulous study and utilization of instruments and methods to achieve three primary goals: separating, quantifying, and identifying [chemical substances](/Chemical_substance). This encompasses both time-honored [classical wet chemistry](/Wet_chemistry) techniques—such as [precipitation](/Precipitation_(chemistry)), [extraction](/Extraction_(chemistry)), [distillation](/Distillation), and simple observational analysis—and more sophisticated modern instrumental techniques, including various forms of [chromatography](/Chromatography), [spectroscopy](/Spectroscopy), and [electrochemistry](/Electrochemistry). It's the detective work of chemistry, often tedious, always critical.

[ångström](/%C3%85ngstr%C3%B6m) (Å)
A non-[SI](/International_System_of_Units), [metric unit](/Metric_system) of [length](/Length) equivalent to 10−10 [metre](/Metre). To put it more accessibly, it’s one ten-billionth of a metre (1&#8260;10,000,000,000 m) or 0.1 [nanometre](/Nanometre). The angstrom, despite its non-SI status, is commonly employed in the [natural sciences](/Natural_science) to express incredibly small, microscopic, or atomic-scale distances. This includes the sizes of atomic nuclei, the [wavelengths](/Wavelength) of [electromagnetic radiation](/Electromagnetic_radiation), and, rather importantly for us, the lengths of [chemical bonds](/Chemical_bond)—for example, the [covalent radius](/Covalent_radius) of a [chlorine](/Chlorine) atom averages about 1 angstrom. It's a unit for details so small they barely register.

[anhydrous](/Anhydrous)
(Of a [substance](/Chemical_substance)) Devoid of [water molecules](/Water_(molecule)), referring particularly to [water of hydration](/Water_of_crystallization). Given that the presence of water can impede or completely derail numerous [chemical processes](/Chemical_process), ensuring [water-free reagents](/Reagent) and techniques is frequently of paramount importance. Anhydrous compounds, being inherently [hygroscopic](/Hygroscopy), tend to gradually absorb water from the surrounding [atmosphere](/Atmosphere_of_Earth) if not properly stored. The opposite, and far less problematic, state is [hydrous](/Hydrous). [4]

[anion](/Anion)
A [negatively charged ion](/Ion). This means it's an [atom](/Atom) or [molecule](/Molecule) that has a net negative [electric charge](/Electric_charge) due to an excess of [electrons](/Electron) compared to its [protons](/Proton). They are attracted to [anodes](/Anode).

[annulation](/Annulation)
The elegant process of constructing a [cyclic compound](/Cyclic_compound) or [ring structure](/Ring_system) from one or more [acyclic precursors](/Open-chain_compound). Alternatively, it can describe a [reaction](/Chemical_reaction) that involves the *addition* of a new ring structure to an existing molecule through the formation of two new [chemical bonds](/Chemical_bond). It’s how chemists build bigger, more complex rings. [2]

[anode](/Anode)
1.&#160;&#160;The [electrode](/Electrode) through which the conventional [electric current](/Electric_current) (defined as the flow of positive charges, because historical conventions are stubborn) *enters* a polarized electrical circuit.
2.&#160;&#160;More specifically, it's the wire or plate within an [electrochemical cell](/Electrochemical_cell) that carries an excess positive charge. Predictably, [negatively charged anions](/Anion) are perpetually drawn towards the anode. The logical opposite, naturally, is the [cathode](/Cathode).

[anomer](/Anomer)
A rather specific term in [carbohydrate chemistry](/Carbohydrate_chemistry). It refers to either of a pair of [cyclic hemiacetal](/Hemiacetal) or [hemiketal](/Hemiketal) [saccharides](/Saccharide) that are [epimers](/Epimer) of each other. The critical distinction lies in their differing configuration at only one [carbon stereocenter](/Stereogenic_center)—specifically, the carbon that bore the [aldehyde](/Aldehyde) or [ketone functional group](/Ketone) in the compound's [acyclic](/Open-chain_compound), [open-chain configuration](/Open-chain_compound). This particular carbon is known as the *anomeric carbon*.

[aprotic](/Aprotic)
(Of a [chemical species](/Chemical_species)) Simply put, *not protic*. This means it is utterly incapable of acting as a [proton donor](/Proton_donor) or readily yielding [protons](/Proton) (H+
) in a [solution](/Solution_(chemistry)). Such species lack acidic hydrogens.

[aqua regia](/Aqua_regia)
A rather notorious [liquid mixture](/Liquid_mixture) of [nitric acid](/Nitric_acid) (HNO3) and [hydrochloric acid](/Hydrochloric_acid) (HCl), optimally in a [molar ratio](/Molar_ratio) of 1:3. It earned its regal name from historical [alchemists](/Alchemist) because of its unique and rather impressive ability to dissolve the so-called [noble metals](/Noble_metal), [gold](/Gold) and [platinum](/Platinum)—metals typically resistant to single acids. It's a testament to the power of synergistic chemical action.

[aquation](/Aquation)
The process by which [water molecules](/Water_(molecule)) perform the critical task of [solvating](/Solvation) or forming [coordination complexes](/Coordination_complex) with [ions](/Ion). It's essentially water wrapping itself around an ion, a fundamental interaction in [aqueous solutions](/Aqueous_solution). [3]

[aqueous solution](/Aqueous_solution)
A [solution](/Solution_(chemistry)) where the [solvent](/Solvent) is, quite simply, [water](/Water_(molecule)). It's the most common and arguably most important type of solution in [chemistry](/Chemistry) and [biology](/Biology). In [chemical equations](/Chemical_equation), its presence is denoted by appending the rather uninspired (aq) to a [chemical formula](/Chemical_formula).

[aromatic](/Aromatic_compound)
(Of a [chemical compound](/Chemical_compound)) Possessing the characteristic property of [aromaticity](/Aromaticity). This implies a cyclic, planar structure with a delocalized [pi electron system](/Pi_electron) that follows [Hückel's rule](/H%C3%BCckel%27s_rule) (4n+2 pi electrons), resulting in unusual [stability](/Chemical_stability) and distinct [chemical properties](/Chemical_property). [Benzene](/Benzene) is the quintessential example.

[aromaticity](/Aromaticity)
A peculiar [chemical property](/Chemical_property) observed in [conjugated rings](/Conjugated_system) of [atoms](/Atom), such as [benzene](/Benzene), which bestows upon them an unusually high degree of [thermodynamic stability](/Chemical_stability) compared to their acyclic counterparts. Such rings are, unsurprisingly, termed [aromatic](/Aromatic_compound). It's a concept that dictates much of [organic chemistry](/Organic_chemistry).

Arrhenius acid
Any [substance](/Chemical_substance) that, when dissolved in [water](/Water_(molecule)), results in an increase in the [concentration](/Concentration) of H+
[ions](/Ion), or, to be more accurate, of [hydronium ions](/Hydronium) (H
3 O+
), within the resulting [aqueous solution](/Aqueous_solution). [1] This definition, while historically significant, is largely superseded by the [Brønsted–Lowry definition](/Br%C3%B8nsted%E2%80%93Lowry_acid%E2%80%93Lowry_acid%E2%80%93base_theory), which is rather similar. It stands in direct [contrast](/Contrast_(linguistics)) to an [Arrhenius base](/Arrhenius_base).

Arrhenius base
Any [substance](/Chemical_substance) that, when dissolved in [water](/Water_(molecule)), causes an increase in the [concentration](/Concentration) of OH−
[ions](/Ion), or, conversely, a decrease in the concentration of [hydronium ions](/Hydronium) (H
3 O+
), within the resulting [aqueous solution](/Aqueous_solution). [1] This definition is, as you might expect, quite similar to that of a [Brønsted–Lowry base](/Br%C3%B8nsted%E2%80%93Lowry_acid%E2%80%93base_theory). It's the antithesis of an [Arrhenius acid](/Arrhenius_acid).

[arrow pushing](/Arrow_pushing)
A representational formalism, a visual language, used in [organic chemistry](/Organic_chemistry) to depict the movement of [electron pairs](/Electron_pair) during [chemical reactions](/Chemical_reaction). Curved arrows show the flow of electrons from an electron-rich site to an electron-poor site, illustrating [reaction mechanisms](/Reaction_mechanism). It's a way to visualize the dynamic dance of electrons, assuming you can follow the choreography.

[aryl](/Aryl)
Any [functional group](/Functional_group) or [substituent](/Substituent) that is derived directly from an [aromatic ring](/Aromatic_compound). Common examples, which you should be familiar with, include [phenyl](/Phenyl) (from [benzene](/Benzene)) or [naphthyl](/Naphthyl) (from [naphthalene](/Naphthalene)). The symbol Ar is frequently employed as a convenient placeholder for a generic aryl group in [structural diagrams](/Structural_formula).

atmolysis
A rather specialized technique for separating a [mixture of gases](/Gas_mixture) by cleverly exploiting their differing [rates of diffusion](/Diffusion). This is typically achieved by allowing the [gases](/Gas) to diffuse through the microscopic pores of a [porous partition](/Porous_medium) or [membrane](/Membrane). It's a subtle form of separation, relying on molecular movement rather than brute force. [3]

[atom](/Atom)
The fundamental building block of a [chemical element](/Chemical_element) in its smallest, indivisible form (at least, chemically indivisible). It is comprised of a dense central [nucleus](/Atomic_nucleus) containing [protons](/Proton) (positively charged) and [neutrons](/Neutron) (electrically neutral), surrounded by a cloud of orbiting [electrons](/Electron) (negatively charged). The number of protons defines the element. Anything smaller is a [subatomic particle](/Subatomic_particle), and that's a whole other field of study.

An [atom](/Atom) with [protons](/Proton), [neutrons](/Neutron), and [electrons](/Electron) labelled.
[atomic mass](/Atomic_mass)
The [mass](/Mass) of an individual [atom](/Atom), typically expressed in [daltons](/Dalton_(unit)) (Da). This value is approximately, but not precisely, equivalent to the [mass number](/Mass_number) (total protons and neutrons) multiplied by one dalton. For elements, the reported atomic mass is often a weighted average of the masses of its naturally occurring [isotopes](/Isotope).

atomic mass unit
See [dalton](/Dalton_(unit)).

[atomic number](/Atomic_number) (Z)
Also known, somewhat redundantly, as *proton number*. This is the absolute count of [protons](/Proton) found within the [nucleus](/Atomic_nucleus) of an [atom](/Atom) belonging to a given [chemical element](/Chemical_element). It is identical to the [charge number](/Charge_number) of the nucleus and serves as the unique identifier for each chemical element on the [periodic table](/Periodic_table_of_the_elements). It's the element's DNA.

[atomic orbital](/Atomic_orbital)
A mathematical function, derived from [quantum mechanics](/Quantum_mechanics), that describes a region of space around the [nucleus](/Atomic_nucleus) of an individual [atom](/Atom) where one or more [electrons](/Electron) are most likely to be found. These orbitals are characterized by specific [energy levels](/Energy_level) and shapes (s, p, d, f), and they are distinct from [molecular orbitals](/Molecular_orbital).

[atomic radius](/Atomic_radius)
A measure of the size of an [atom](/Atom), typically defined as the distance from the [nucleus](/Atomic_nucleus) to the outermost stable [electron orbital](/Atomic_orbital) in a neutral atom. This value is not absolute but depends on how it's measured (e.g., [covalent radius](/Covalent_radius), [ionic radius](/Ionic_radius), [van der Waals radius](/Van_der_Waals_radius)) and the atom's [chemical environment](/Chemical_environment).

atomic weight
See [relative atomic mass](/Relative_atomic_mass). A term that, for clarity, should probably be retired.

[atomicity](/Atomicity_(chemistry))
The total count of [atoms](/Atom) that are present within a single [molecule](/Molecule) of a given [substance](/Chemical_substance). For example, a molecule of [ozone](/Ozone) (O3) exhibits an atomicity of 3, while the more complex [benzene](/Benzene) (C6H6) has an atomicity of 12. It's a simple count, nothing profound. [3]

[autoignition temperature](/Autoignition_temperature)
Also called the *kindling point*. This is the lowest [temperature](/Temperature) at which a specific [substance](/Chemical_substance) will spontaneously ignite in a normal [atmosphere](/Atmosphere_of_Earth) *without* the need for an external source of ignition, such as a [flame](/Flame) or [spark](/Spark). Essentially, the ambient temperature alone provides sufficient [activation energy](/Activation_energy) for [combustion](/Combustion) to commence. Substances that achieve this spontaneous ignition at naturally occurring temperatures are, rather dramatically, termed [pyrophoric](/Pyrophoricity). Do not confuse this with [ignition temperature](/Ignition_temperature), which typically implies an external ignition source.

[Avogadro constant](/Avogadro_constant) (NA)
The ratio that defines the number of discrete [constituent particles](/Constituent_particle) (such as [molecules](/Molecule), [atoms](/Atom), or [ions](/Ion)) to the [amount of a substance](/Amount_of_substance). It is precisely defined as 6.02214076×10^23&#160;mol−1. This value is fundamental to converting between the macroscopic world of grams and the microscopic world of atoms and molecules.

[Avogadro number](/Avogadro_number)
The specific number of discrete [constituent particles](/Constituent_particle) found within one [mole](/Mole_(unit)) of a [substance](/Chemical_substance), defined as exactly 6.02214076×10^23. This is a [dimensionless number](/Dimensionless_quantity), and it is crucial to note its distinction from the [Avogadro constant](/Avogadro_constant), which carries a unit (mol−1).

[Avogadro's law](/Avogadro%27s_law)
A fundamental [gas law](/Gas_laws) stating that, under conditions of constant [temperature](/Temperature) and [pressure](/Pressure), equal [volumes](/Volume) of all [gases](/Gas) contain the same number of [molecules](/Molecule). It's a rather elegant simplicity in the behavior of ideal gases.

[azeotrope](/Azeotrope)
A peculiar [mixture of liquids](/Liquid_mixture) whose [chemical composition](/Chemical_composition) remains stubbornly unchanged even when subjected to [distillation](/Distillation). This means they boil at a constant temperature, and their [vapor phase](/Vapor_phase) has the same composition as their [liquid phase](/Liquid_phase), making them inseparable by simple distillation. It's a headache for purification.

