B

balance
A precision instrument used for measuring [mass](/Mass). Not to be confused with a scale, which measures weight. Accuracy in terminology, please.

backbone
Also known, more descriptively, as the *main chain*. This refers to the primary, most structurally significant portion of a [molecule](/Molecule), especially when considered in relation to its other parts, [functional groups](/Functional_group), [moieties](/Moiety_(chemistry)), or [substituents](/Substituent). In the context of a [polymer](/Polymer), it designates the linear chain of [atoms](/Atom) to which all other chains (whether long, short, or both) can be regarded as being attached as [pendant groups](/Pendant_group) or [side chains](/Side_chain). Should there be multiple chains that could equally claim the title of backbone, the one that facilitates the most straightforward representation of the molecule in [chemical formulae](/Chemical_formula) and [nomenclature](/Chemical_nomenclature) is, by convention, deemed the backbone. It’s the core structure, the foundation upon which everything else hangs. [2]

[barometer](/Barometer)
A rather ingenious device, first conceived by [Evangelista Torricelli](/Evangelista_Torricelli), employed to accurately measure [atmospheric pressure](/Atmospheric_pressure). Essential for any serious work involving [gases](/Gas).

[base](/Base_(chemistry))
A [substance](/Chemical_substance) defined by its capacity to accept a [proton](/Proton) (in the Brønsted-Lowry sense) and, in [aqueous solution](/Aqueous_solution), exhibit a [pH](/PH) value exceeding 7.0. A ubiquitous example, which you should certainly know, is [sodium hydroxide](/Sodium_hydroxide) (NaOH). Like [acids](/Acid), bases are fundamental to innumerable [chemical reactions](/Chemical_reaction).

[base anhydride](/Base_anhydride)
An [oxide](/Oxide) of a Group I or Group II [metal element](/Metal), meaning it's derived from a [base](/Base_(chemistry)) by the removal of [water](/Water_(molecule)). It's the counterpart to an [acid anhydride](/Acid_anhydride).

[basic](/Basic_(chemistry))
Possessing the characteristic properties of a [base](/Base_(chemistry)). In [aqueous solution](/Aqueous_solution), this means a [pH](/PH) greater than 7.0. It's the opposite of [acidic](/Acidic), again, a concept that shouldn't require excessive contemplation.

[basicity](/Basicity)
A quantitative measure of the capacity of a [base](/Base_(chemistry)) to accept [protons](/Proton) or donate [electron pairs](/Electron_pair). It can also refer to the number of acidic hydrogens that an [acid](/Acid) can lose, or the number of hydroxyl groups a base contains.

[battery](/Electrochemical_battery)
More precisely, an [electrochemical battery](/Electrochemical_battery) is a device that stores [chemical energy](/Chemical_energy) and converts it into [electrical energy](/Electrical_energy) through [redox reactions](/Redox). It typically consists of one or more [electrochemical cells](/Electrochemical_cell) connected in series or parallel.

[beaker](/Beaker_(glassware))
A ubiquitous [cylindrical vessel](/Cylinder) or container, invariably with a flat bottom, and most commonly fabricated from [glassware](/Glassware). It finds widespread application in laboratories for a multitude of purposes: preparing, holding, containing, collecting, or even crudely measuring [chemicals](/Chemical_species), [samples](/Sample_(material)), or [solutions](/Solution_(chemistry)). It also frequently serves as the reaction chamber where a [chemical reaction](/Chemical_reaction) is allowed to unfold. Beakers are easily distinguished from [flasks](/Laboratory_flask) by their straight, rather than sloping, sides; most also feature a small spout on the rim, a thoughtful design choice to facilitate pouring without excessive spillage. A fundamental, if unglamorous, piece of lab equipment.

[Beer–Lambert law](/Beer%E2%80%93Lambert_law)
A fundamental empirical relationship in [spectroscopy](/Spectroscopy) that correlates the [absorbance](/Absorbance) of [light](/Light) by a [solution](/Solution_(chemistry)) to the properties of the solution itself. Specifically, it states that the absorbance is directly proportional to the [concentration](/Concentration) of the absorbing [species](/Chemical_species) and the [path length](/Path_length) of the light through the solution. Crucial for quantitative analysis, assuming you can keep your cuvettes clean.

[biochemistry](/Biochemistry)
The intricate and utterly fascinating study of the [chemistry](/Chemistry) that underpins all [biological systems](/Biological_system) and [organisms](/Organism). It delves into the structure, function, and interactions of [biomolecules](/Biomolecule) (like [proteins](/Protein), [nucleic acids](/Nucleic_acid), [carbohydrates](/Carbohydrate), and [lipids](/Lipid)) and the [chemical processes](/Chemical_process) that sustain [life](/Life). It’s where chemistry truly gets interesting, or at least, complex enough to warrant attention.

[Bohr model](/Bohr_model)
Also known as the *Rutherford–Bohr model*. A foundational, though ultimately simplified, model for the general structure of the [atom](/Atom), collaboratively proposed by [Niels Bohr](/Niels_Bohr) and [Ernest Rutherford](/Ernest_Rutherford) in 1913. It posited a small, dense [nucleus](/Atomic_nucleus) composed of positively charged [particles](/Particle) (protons and neutrons, though neutrons were discovered later) encircled by [electrons](/Electron) orbiting in discrete, quantized [energy levels](/Energy_level). These electrons are, predictably, attracted to the nucleus by [electrostatic forces](/Electrostatic_force). This interpretation revolutionized atomic theory, replacing several earlier, less accurate hypotheses and swiftly becoming the prevailing standard model for depicting atomic structure, even if it has since been refined by [quantum mechanics](/Quantum_mechanics).

[boiling](/Boiling)
Also known, somewhat dramatically, as *ebullition*. This is a more rapid, intensely energetic form of [vaporization](/Vaporization), a stark contrast to the much slower, quiescent process of simple evaporation. During boiling, a [substance](/Chemical_substance) undergoes a distinct [phase transition](/Phase_transition) from a [liquid](/Liquid) to a [gas](/Gas). It occurs specifically when a liquid is heated to its [boiling point](/Boiling_point), at which temperature the liquid's internal [vapor pressure](/Vapor_pressure) surpasses the external [pressure](/Pressure) exerted upon it by the surrounding [atmosphere](/Atmosphere_of_Earth). This pressure differential causes the gaseous phase to separate from the liquid phase rapidly, often with considerable, and sometimes violent, effervescence.

[boiling flask](/Boiling_flask)
Also known, more charmingly, as a *Florence flask*. This is a specific type of [laboratory flask](/Laboratory_flask), typically crafted from [glass](/Glass), characterized by a large, spherical body, a relatively long, narrow neck, and a flat bottom. Its design is particularly optimized for heating, boiling, and distilling [liquids](/Liquid), and its rounded shape makes swirling the contents remarkably easy without spillage. See also [round-bottom flask](/Round-bottom_flask), which is similar but lacks the flat bottom.

[boiling point](/Boiling_point)
Also known as the *vaporization point*. This is the precise [temperature](/Temperature) at which a [substance](/Chemical_substance) undergoes a [phase transition](/Phase_transition) from a [liquid](/Liquid) state to a [gas](/Gas) (or [vapor](/Vapor)). It is inherently dependent on external [pressure](/Pressure) and is therefore usually specified for a given substance under [standard conditions](/Standard_conditions_of_temperature_and_pressure). It's a critical [physical property](/Physical_property) for identifying and separating compounds.

[boiling-point elevation](/Boiling-point_elevation)
The phenomenon by which the [boiling point](/Boiling_point) of a [solvent](/Solvent) is observed to increase when a non-volatile [solute](/Solute) is dissolved within it. This is a [colligative property](/Colligative_property), meaning it depends on the number of solute particles, not their identity. It's a consequence of the solute reducing the solvent's [vapor pressure](/Vapor_pressure).

[bond](/Chemical_bond)
Any persistent, enduring [attraction](/Attraction) that exists between [atoms](/Atom), [ions](/Ion), or [molecules](/Molecule), which ultimately enables the formation of [chemical compounds](/Chemical_compound). These bonds arise from a vast array of [electrochemical forces](/Electrochemical_force), whose strengths can vary immensely. They are broken only when these attractive forces are overcome by other, more potent forces (e.g., thermal energy). The specific types, intrinsic strengths, and sheer quantities of bonds holding together [chemical substances](/Chemical_substance) are the fundamental determinants of the overall structure and macroscopic [bulk properties](/Bulk_properties) of [matter](/Matter). Without bonds, nothing would exist as we know it.

[bond angle](/Bond_angle)
The geometric angle formed between two adjacent [covalent bonds](/Covalent_bond) originating from the same [atom](/Atom) within a [molecule](/Molecule). This angle is a crucial determinant of [molecular geometry](/Molecular_geometry) and is influenced by [electron-pair repulsion](/VSEPR_theory).

[Boyle's law](/Boyle%27s_law)
A classical [gas law](/Gas_laws) which rather elegantly states that, for a given [mass](/Mass) of [gas](/Gas) maintained at a constant [temperature](/Temperature), its [volume](/Volume) is inversely proportional to its [pressure](/Pressure). Reduce the volume, pressure goes up; increase the volume, pressure goes down. Simple, yet profoundly important.

[Bragg's law](/Bragg%27s_law)
A fundamental principle in [X-ray crystallography](/X-ray_scattering_techniques) that describes the conditions for [constructive interference](/Constructive_interference) of [X-rays](/X-ray) diffracted by a [crystal lattice](/Crystal_structure). It relates the angle of incidence, the wavelength of the X-rays, and the interplanar spacing of the crystal to produce a measurable [diffraction pattern](/Diffraction_pattern). Essential for determining [crystal structures](/Crystal_structure).

bridge
A [chemical bond](/Chemical_bond) (or, less commonly, an [atom](/Atom) or an unbranched chain of atoms) that serves to connect two distinct parts of the *same* [molecule](/Molecule). Essentially, it's an [intramolecular bond](/Intramolecular_force) that links different [moieties](/Moiety_(chemistry)) or [functional groups](/Functional_group) within a larger structure. [2]

bridgehead
Either of the two [tertiary atoms](/Tertiary_carbon) that, by forming [bonds](/Chemical_bond) with each other, create an [intramolecular bridge](/Bridge_(chemistry)) within a [molecule](/Molecule). These atoms are often part of fused or bridged ring systems and have specific [stereochemical constraints](/Stereochemistry). [2]

[Brønsted–Lowry acid](/Br%C3%B8nsted%E2%80%93Lowry_acid%E2%80%93base_theory)
Any [chemical species](/Chemical_species) that, with remarkable generosity, readily donates a [proton](/Proton) (H+
). This is one of the more widely used definitions of an [acid](/Acid).

[Brønsted–Lowry acid–base reaction](/Br%C3%B8nsted%E2%80%93Lowry_acid%E2%80%93base_theory)
A [chemical reaction](/Chemical_reaction) characterized by the transfer of a [proton](/Proton) from a [Brønsted–Lowry acid](/Br%C3%B8nsted%E2%80%93Lowry_acid%E2%80%93base_theory) to a [Brønsted–Lowry base](/Br%C3%B8nsted%E2%80%93Lowry_acid%E2%80%93base_theory). It's a fundamental concept in understanding [acid–base chemistry](/Acid%E2%80%93base_reaction).

[Brønsted–Lowry base](/Br%C3%B8nsted%E2%80%93Lowry_acid%E2%80%93base_theory)
Any [chemical species](/Chemical_species) that, with equal readiness, accepts a [proton](/Proton) (H+
). This is the complementary definition to a [Brønsted–Lowry acid](/Br%C3%B8nsted%E2%80%93Lowry_acid%E2%80%93base_theory).

[Brownian motion](/Brownian_motion)
The erratic, seemingly random movement of [particles](/Particle) suspended in a [fluid](/Fluid) (a [liquid](/Liquid) or a [gas](/Gas)) resulting from their collision with the fast-moving [atoms](/Atom) or [molecules](/Molecule) in the fluid. First observed by [Robert Brown](/Robert_Brown_(botanist)), it provides compelling evidence for the existence of atoms and molecules and is a manifestation of [thermal energy](/Thermal_energy).

[Büchner flask](/B%C3%BCchner_flask)
A type of heavy-walled [laboratory flask](/Laboratory_flask), typically made of [glass](/Glass), with a side arm for connection to a [vacuum source](/Vacuum_pump). It is specifically designed for [vacuum filtration](/Vacuum_filtration) in conjunction with a [Büchner funnel](/B%C3%BCchner_funnel), allowing for rapid separation of solids from liquids.

[buffered solution](/Buffered_solution)
Also known, more simply, as a *buffer*. This is an [aqueous solution](/Aqueous_solution) meticulously prepared to consist of a [weak acid](/Weak_acid) and its [conjugate base](/Conjugate_base), or, conversely, a [weak base](/Weak_base) and its [conjugate acid](/Conjugate_acid). Its defining characteristic is its remarkable ability to resist significant changes in [pH](/PH) when small amounts of [strong acids](/Strong_acid) or [bases](/Base_(chemistry)) are added. Essential for maintaining stable pH environments in [biological systems](/Biological_system) and many chemical processes.

[bumping](/Bumping_(chemistry))
A rather annoying and potentially dangerous phenomenon in which a homogeneous [liquid](/Liquid), when heated to its [boiling point](/Boiling_point), becomes [superheated](/Superheating) (i.e., its temperature rises above its boiling point without actually boiling). Upon the sudden formation of a [nucleation](/Nucleation) site (like a tiny scratch or trapped air bubble), the superheated liquid rapidly and violently boils to the [gas phase](/Gas_phase), resulting in an abrupt and often forceful expulsion of the liquid from its container. In extreme, and rather inconvenient, cases, the container itself may shatter. This can be mitigated by frequent stirring, selecting an appropriate container, and, most effectively, by adding [boiling chips](/Boiling_chip) to provide continuous nucleation sites.

[bung](/Bung)
Also known as a *stopper* or *cork*. This is a cylindrical or conical plug or closure, typically made of rubber or cork, used to create a seal for a container such as a bottle, test tube, [flask](/Laboratory_flask), or barrel. Its purpose is, predictably, to prevent spillage or evaporation.

[burette](/Burette)
Also spelled *buret*. A precision piece of [glassware](/Glassware) equipped with a stopcock at the bottom and precise volumetric markings, specifically designed to dispense highly accurate and specific amounts of [liquid](/Liquid). Its primary use is in procedures where exceptional volumetric precision is paramount, such as during [titrations](/Titration) or other [resource-dependent reactions](/Chemical_reaction).

[butyl](/Butyl)
A common, non-systematic name for an [alkyl functional group](/Alkyl_group) derived from either of the two [isomers](/Isomer) of [butane](/Butane). It carries the generic [chemical formula](/Chemical_formula) –C4H9. This group can exist as a [substituent](/Substituent) within [organic compounds](/Organic_compound) or, less commonly, as an independent [ion](/Ion) or [radical](/Radical_(chemistry)). In [IUPAC nomenclature](/Chemical_nomenclature), the presence of a butyl substituent is indicated by the prefix "butyl" in the compound's name, or by the abbreviation "Bu" in [chemical formulae](/Chemical_formula). For example, [butyl alcohol](/Butyl_alcohol) (butanol), which can exist in five different isomeric forms depending on the arrangement of its four carbon atoms, is often written with the generic formula CH4CH9OH or BuOH. It’s a slightly more complex alkyl group, but still rather straightforward.

