C

[calorific value](/Calorific_value)
A quantitative measure of the amount of [heat](/Heat) [energy](/Energy) released per unit [mass](/Mass) when a given [substance](/Chemical_substance) undergoes complete [combustion](/Combustion). It is typically expressed in units of [megajoules per kilogram](/Joule) (MJ/kg) or [kilojoules per gram](/Joule) (kJ/g). This value is crucial for assessing the [energy content](/Energy_content) of [fuels](/Fuel). [3]

[calorimeter](/Calorimeter)
Any of various devices meticulously designed and employed to measure [thermal properties](/Thermal_properties) (i.e., [heat](/Heat)). This includes determining [calorific values](/Calorific_value) or the [heats of chemical reactions](/Heat_of_reaction). It's essentially a thermally isolated system, allowing for the precise measurement of heat exchange, assuming you've assembled it correctly. [3]

[calx](/Calx)
A rather archaic term for a [metal oxide](/Metal_oxide) that is formed when a [metal ore](/Ore) is heated in the presence of [air](/Air). It's the product of early [metallurgy](/Metallurgy) and [alchemy](/Alchemy). [3]

[carbanion](/Carbanion)
Any [organic ion](/Organic_ion) that bears a net negative [electric charge](/Electric_charge) specifically on a [carbon atom](/Carbon). Its general formula is typically R3C−
. Carbanions are frequently encountered as highly [reactive intermediate](/Reactive_intermediate) species in certain [organic reactions](/Organic_reaction), playing a crucial role in forming new carbon-carbon bonds. It's the negatively charged carbon's moment in the spotlight. [3] Contrast [carbocation](/Carbocation).

[carbide](/Carbide)
A distinct class of [interstitial compounds](/Interstitial_compound) composed of [carbon](/Carbon) [bonded](/Chemical_bond) to a particular [metal](/Metal) (typically a large-radius [transition metal](/Transition_metal)) within a densely packed [crystal lattice](/Crystal_structure). In this arrangement, the carbon [atoms](/Atom) occupy the small spaces (interstices) between the larger metal atoms. [Tungsten carbide](/Tungsten_carbide) (WC) is a well-known example, prized for its extreme hardness.

[carbocation](/Carbocation)
Any [organic ion](/Organic_ion) that bears a net positive [electric charge](/Electric_charge) specifically on a [carbon atom](/Carbon). Its general formula is typically R3C+
. Carbocations are highly [reactive intermediate](/Reactive_intermediate) species in many [organic reactions](/Organic_reaction), acting as [electrophiles](/Electrophile) due to their electron deficiency. They are the positively charged carbon's fleeting claim to fame. Contrast [carbanion](/Carbanion).

[carbon](/Carbon)
The sixth [chemical element](/Chemical_element) on the [periodic table](/Periodic_table_of_the_elements), with the symbol C. It is a [non-metal](/Non-metal) and is absolutely fundamental to all known [life](/Life), forming the backbone of [organic compounds](/Organic_compound) through its unique ability to form stable [covalent bonds](/Covalent_bond) with itself and many other elements. Its [allotropes](/Allotrope) include [diamond](/Diamond) and [graphite](/Graphite). Without it, you wouldn't be here, so perhaps show some respect.

[carbonic acid](/Carbonic_acid)
A [weak inorganic acid](/Weak_acid) with the [chemical formula](/Chemical_formula) H2CO3. It forms when [carbon dioxide](/Carbon_dioxide) dissolves in [water](/Water_(molecule)). It's responsible for the fizz in carbonated drinks and plays a role in [ocean acidification](/Ocean_acidification).

[carbonization](/Carbonization)
1.&#160;&#160;The transformative process by which [organic compounds](/Organic_compound), such as those found within [biological organisms](/Biological_organism), are converted into other forms of [carbon](/Carbon) or [carbonic residues](/Carbonaceous_residue). This can occur through heating, burning, or over geological timescales during [fossilization](/Fossilization).
2.&#160;&#160;More broadly, it refers to the process of coating a [substance](/Chemical_substance) with carbon residues (like [charcoal](/Charcoal)) or causing a substance to become scorched, blackened, or charred. It's essentially the art of turning things to carbon.

[carbonyl](/Carbonyl)
1.&#160;&#160;A ubiquitous [functional group](/Functional_group) composed of a [carbon atom](/Carbon) [double-bonded](/Double_bond) to an [oxygen atom](/Oxygen), represented by the formula C=O. Carbonyl groups are central to many classes of [organic compounds](/Organic_compound), including [aldehydes](/Aldehyde), [ketones](/Ketone), [carboxylic acids](/Carboxylic_acid), and [esters](/Ester), and they often form part of larger functional groups. Its reactivity is pivotal in organic synthesis.
2.&#160;&#160;In a different context, it can refer to an [inorganic](/Inorganic_compound) or [organometallic coordination complex](/Organometallic_chemistry) where [carbon monoxide](/Carbon_monoxide) acts as a [ligand](/Ligand) (e.g., a [metal carbonyl](/Metal_carbonyl)). Context is, as always, everything.

[carboxyl](/Carboxyl)
A [functional group](/Functional_group) consisting of a [carbonyl group](/Carbonyl) (C=O) and a [hydroxyl group](/Hydroxy_group) (–OH) attached to the same [carbon atom](/Carbon). Its formula is –COOH. It is the defining characteristic of [carboxylic acids](/Carboxylic_acid) and is responsible for their acidic properties.

[carboxylic acid](/Carboxylic_acid)
A prominent class of [organic acids](/Organic_acid) and a defining [functional group](/Functional_group) characterized by a [carboxyl group](/Carboxyl) (–COOH) attached to a [substituent group](/Substituent). Carboxylic acids adhere to the general formula R–COOH (also conveniently written as R–CO2H), where R can be an [alkyl](/Alkyl_group), [alkenyl](/Alkene), [aryl](/Aryl), or any other carbon-containing substituent. They are typically [weak acids](/Weak_acid) but play crucial roles in [biochemistry](/Biochemistry) and industrial processes.

The skeletal formula for a generic [carboxylic acid](/Carboxylic_acid), with R denoting a variable carbon-containing [substituent group](/Substituent).
[CAS Registry Number](/CAS_Registry_Number) (CAS RN)
Also known, more simply, as a *CAS Number*. This is a unique numerical identifier, rather diligently assigned by the [Chemical Abstracts Service](/Chemical_Abstracts_Service) (CAS), to virtually every [chemical substance](/Chemical_substance) that has ever been described in the open scientific literature. This includes an astonishingly vast collection of over 182 million [organic](/Organic_compound) and [inorganic compounds](/Inorganic_compound), [minerals](/Mineral), [isotopes](/Isotope), [alloys](/Alloy), [polymers](/Polymer), and [mixtures](/Mixture), as well as the somewhat vaguely defined "UVCBs" (substances of unknown or variable composition, complex reaction products, or biological origin). CAS numbers are an internationally recognized standard, providing an unambiguous identification system used by scientists, industries, and regulatory bodies alike. It’s the chemical world’s equivalent of a social security number, only far more useful. [5]

[catalyst](/Catalyst)
Any [element](/Chemical_element) or [compound](/Chemical_compound) that, with remarkable efficiency, facilitates an *increase* in the [rate](/Reaction_rate) of a [chemical reaction](/Chemical_reaction) *without* itself being consumed or destroyed during the reaction. It participates, but it doesn't get used up. It's therefore considered both a [reactant](/Reactant) and a [product](/Product_(chemistry)) of the reaction, a rather unique duality. [Enzymes](/Enzyme) are biological catalysts.

[cathode](/Cathode)
An [electrode](/Electrode) from which the conventional [electric current](/Electric_current) (the flow of positive charges, again, stubborn conventions) *exits* a polarized electrical circuit. Predictably, positively charged [cations](/Cation) are always drawn towards the cathode. However, the cathode's actual [polarity](/Electric_polarity) (positive or negative) can vary, depending on the specific type of electrical device and how it is being operated. It’s the counterpart to the [anode](/Anode).

[cation](/Cation)
A [positively charged ion](/Ion). This means it's an [atom](/Atom) or [molecule](/Molecule) that has lost one or more [electrons](/Electron) from its neutral state, resulting in a net positive [electric charge](/Electric_charge). They are attracted to [cathodes](/Cathode).

[cell potential](/Resting_potential)
More accurately, [electromotive force](/Electromotive_force) (emf) or [electrode potential](/Electrode_potential). This is the driving force, measured in [volts](/Volt), within a [galvanic cell](/Galvanic_cell) (a type of [electrochemical cell](/Electrochemical_cell)) that effectively "pulls" [electrons](/Electron) from a [reducing agent](/Reducing_agent) (where [oxidation](/Oxidation) occurs) towards an [oxidizing agent](/Oxidizing_agent) (where [reduction](/Reduction_(chemistry)) occurs). It's the measure of the cell's ability to do electrical work.

[centrifugation](/Centrifugation)
A common [laboratory technique](/Laboratory_technique) that involves the application of [centrifugal force](/Centrifugal_force) to separate [particles](/Particle) from a [solution](/Solution_(chemistry)). This separation occurs based on differences in their size, shape, and, crucially, their [density](/Density). Larger and/or denser substances will migrate away from the axis of the [centrifuge](/Centrifuge), while smaller and/or less dense substances will migrate towards the axis. It’s a powerful method for isolating components in a mixture.

[centrifuge](/Centrifuge)
A mechanical device specifically designed to perform [centrifugation](/Centrifugation). It achieves separation of [substances](/Chemical_substance) based on their size, shape, and [density](/Density) by rapidly rotating vessels containing the substances around a central axis at extremely high velocities. It's a rather effective, if sometimes noisy, way to separate things.

[chain reaction](/Chain_reaction)
A [chemical reaction](/Chemical_reaction) (or [nuclear reaction](/Nuclear_reaction)) where the products of one step in the reaction become the [reactants](/Reactant) for the next step, leading to a self-propagating series of events that can rapidly accelerate. [Nuclear fission](/Nuclear_fission) and the combustion of [hydrocarbons](/Hydrocarbon) are classic examples.

[charge number](/Charge_number)
A [quantized](/Quantification_(science)) value representing [electric charge](/Electric_charge). It is calculated by dividing the electric charge (measured in [coulombs](/Coulomb)) by the [elementary-charge constant](/Elementary_charge) (e), or z = q / e. For [ions](/Ion), charge numbers are denoted in superscript (e.g., Na+
indicates a [sodium ion](/Sodium_ion) with a charge number of positive one). [Atomic numbers](/Atomic_number) are, in essence, the charge numbers of [atomic nuclei](/Atomic_nucleus).

[Charles's law](/Charles%27s_law)
A classical [gas law](/Gas_laws) which states that when the [pressure](/Pressure) on a [sample](/Sample_(material)) of a dry [gas](/Gas) is held absolutely constant, its [Kelvin temperature](/Kelvin) is directly proportional to its [volume](/Volume). Heat it up, it expands; cool it down, it contracts (assuming constant pressure). Another fundamental, and rather obvious, observation about gases.

[chelating agent](/Chelating_agent)
An [organic compound](/Organic_compound), often referred to as a [chelant](/Chelant) or [chelator](/Chelator), that possesses multiple [donor atoms](/Donor_atom) capable of forming two or more separate [coordinate covalent bonds](/Coordinate_covalent_bond) with a single central [metal ion](/Metal_ion). This multi-point attachment results in a stable ring-like structure, known as a [chelate complex](/Chelate).

[chelation](/Chelation)
A specific type of [bonding](/Chemical_bond) interaction that involves the formation of *two or more separate [coordinate covalent bonds](/Coordinate_covalent_bond)* between a [polydentate ligand](/Polydentate_ligand) (a molecule with multiple sites capable of donating [electron pairs](/Electron_pair)) and a single central [metal ion](/Metal_ion). The ligand is typically an [organic compound](/Organic_compound) referred to as a [chelant](/Chelant) or [chelating agent](/Chelating_agent). This results in a more stable complex compared to monodentate ligands.

chemical
See [chemical species](/Chemical_species) and [chemical compound](/Chemical_compound). A term often used loosely, to my perpetual irritation.

chemical bond
See [bond](/Chemical_bond).

[chemical composition](/Chemical_composition)
The precise identity and the relative number of the [elements](/Chemical_element) that constitute a [chemical compound](/Chemical_compound) or [mixture](/Mixture). This information is frequently, and conveniently, expressed using a [chemical formula](/Chemical_formula). It tells you what something is made of.

chemical compound
See [compound](/Chemical_compound).

[chemical decomposition](/Chemical_decomposition)
The process by which a single [particle](/Particle) or [molecular entity](/Molecular_entity) (such as a [molecule](/Molecule) or a [reactive intermediate](/Reactive_intermediate)) breaks down or separates into two or more distinct fragments. Alternatively, it refers to a [chemical reaction](/Chemical_reaction) where two or more [products](/Product_(chemistry)) are formed from a single [reactant](/Reactant). It's the opposite of [chemical synthesis](/Chemical_synthesis).

chemical element
See [element](/Chemical_element).

[chemical formula](/Chemical_formula)
Any of various standardized methods for concisely displaying information about the [chemical composition](/Chemical_composition) of a [compound](/Chemical_compound) or [molecule](/Molecule), utilizing a combination of letters (element symbols), numbers (stoichiometric ratios), and/or typographical symbols. While chemical formulas, such as [empirical](/Empirical_formula) and [molecular formulas](/Molecular_formula), can only convey the identities and numerical proportions of the [atoms](/Atom) within a compound, they are thus more limited in their descriptive power than full [chemical names](/Chemical_nomenclature) or detailed [structural formulas](/Structural_formula). They are a shorthand, useful but incomplete.

[chemical law](/Chemical_law)
A [law of nature](/Physical_law) that governs the behavior and interactions of [matter](/Matter) at the [atomic](/Atom) and [molecular](/Molecule) level, providing fundamental principles for [chemistry](/Chemistry). A classic example is the [law of conservation of mass](/Law_of_conservation_of_mass). These are not suggestions; they are inviolable rules.

[chemical nomenclature](/Chemical_nomenclature)
The systematic process of naming [chemical compounds](/Chemical_compound) and [chemical species](/Chemical_species) according to established rules, primarily those set by the [IUPAC](/International_Union_of_Pure_and_Applied_Chemistry). Its purpose is to provide unambiguous and universally understood names for the vast array of chemical entities. It's tedious but necessary to avoid utter chaos.

[chemical physics](/Chemical_physics)
A distinct branch of [science](/Science) that sits at the intersection of [chemistry](/Chemistry) and [physics](/Physics). It applies the principles and techniques of [physics](/Physics) to understand [chemical phenomena](/Chemical_phenomenon) at the [atomic](/Atom) and [molecular](/Molecule) level. Unlike [physical chemistry](/Physical_chemistry), it often focuses more on fundamental physical processes that govern chemical systems.

[chemical process](/Chemical_process)
1.&#160;&#160;Any method or means by which one or more [chemicals](/Chemical_species) or [chemical compounds](/Chemical_compound) undergo a change in any way, whether occurring naturally or artificially induced, spontaneously or through the application of external forces. It's a broad term for any transformation.
2.&#160;&#160;In the specialized field of [chemical engineering](/Chemical_engineering), this term specifically refers to any method employed on an industrial scale (particularly within [manufacturing](/Manufacturing)) to alter the [composition](/Chemical_composition) of one or more [chemicals](/Chemical_species) or [materials](/Material).

[chemical reaction](/Chemical_reaction)
The fundamental process involving the rearrangement of [atoms](/Atom) and [molecules](/Molecule), resulting in the transformation of one or more [substances](/Chemical_substance) (the [reactants](/Reactant)) into one or more *different* substances (the [products](/Product_(chemistry))). This always involves the breaking and/or formation of [chemical bonds](/Chemical_bond). It's how everything changes.

[chemical species](/Chemical_species)
Also known, somewhat generically, as simply a *chemical*. This refers to a [chemical substance](/Chemical_substance) or an ensemble of substances composed of chemically identical [molecular entities](/Molecular_entity). These entities are capable of exploring the same set of [molecular energy levels](/Molecular_orbital) within a characteristic or delineated [time scale](/Time_scale). It's a precise term for a distinct chemical entity, a concept often misused by the uninitiated.

[chemical substance](/Chemical_substance)
Also known as a *pure substance* or, rather lazily, simply a *substance*. This is a form of [matter](/Matter) that possesses a constant [chemical composition](/Chemical_composition) and a unique set of characteristic [properties](/Property). Crucially, it cannot be separated into simpler components by purely [physical methods](/Physical_method) (i.e., without disrupting [chemical bonds](/Chemical_bond)). It is frequently referred to as a "pure substance" to clearly distinguish it from a [mixture](/Mixture).

[chemical synthesis](/Chemical_synthesis)
The deliberate, artificial execution of one or more [chemical reactions](/Chemical_reaction) with the explicit goal of obtaining one or more desired [products](/Product_(chemistry)). In contemporary [laboratory contexts](/Laboratory), well-designed chemical syntheses are expected to be both reliable and reproducible. It's the art and science of making new things.

[chemistry](/Chemistry)
The [scientific discipline](/Scientific_discipline) that, for some inexplicable reason, dedicates itself to the study of [chemical substances](/Chemical_substance), [compounds](/Chemical_compound), and [molecules](/Molecule)—all of which are composed of [atoms](/Atom) from various [chemical elements](/Chemical_element). It meticulously examines their [compositions](/Chemical_composition), [structures](/Molecular_structure), [properties](/Chemical_property), observed [behaviors](/Chemical_behavior), and, most importantly, the profound changes they undergo during [reactions](/Chemical_reaction) with other substances. It's the study of everything around you, and within you.

[chirality](/Chirality_(chemistry))
A fundamental property of [asymmetry](/Asymmetry) inherent in a [molecule](/Molecule) or [ion](/Ion) that renders it distinguishable from its [mirror image](/Mirror_image). This distinction means that the molecule cannot be superimposed upon its reflection by any combination of simple [geometric rotations](/Rotation_(mathematics)), [translations](/Translation_(geometry)), or even some [conformational changes](/Conformation_(chemistry)). [6] [7] Such a molecule or ion is deemed *chiral*, and it invariably exists in two distinct forms, known as [enantiomers](/Enantiomer), which are [stereoisomers](/Stereoisomer) of each other. These forms are differentiated as either "right-handed" or "left-handed" based on their [absolute configuration](/Absolute_configuration) or some other established criterion. Various forms of asymmetry can give rise to chirality, most commonly when molecules possess [stereogenic elements](/Stereogenic_element) such as one or more [stereocenters](/Stereogenic_center) (central chirality), a [stereogenic axis](/Axial_chirality) (axial chirality), or a [stereogenic plane](/Planar_chirality) (planar chirality); additionally, the intrinsic curvature of a molecule can also impart inherent chirality. It's a property that profoundly impacts biological activity, proving that sometimes, being a mirror image isn't enough.

Structural diagrams of two [chiral molecules](/Chirality_(chemistry)), the non-superposable mirror-image [enantiomers](/Enantiomer) (S)-[alanine](/Alanine) (left) and (R)-alanine (right). Despite having identical [structural formulas](/Structural_formula) and the same [physical properties](/Physical_property) (except for [optical activity](/Optical_activity)), they are nonetheless distinct [chemicals](/Chemical_species) and exhibit differential reactivity with other chiral compounds.

[chromatography](/Chromatography)
A powerful and versatile family of [laboratory techniques](/Laboratory_technique) used for the [separation](/Separation_process) of [mixtures](/Mixture). It operates on the principle that components of a mixture will move at different rates through a stationary phase when carried by a mobile phase, based on differences in their [adsorption](/Adsorption), [solubility](/Solubility), or other [physical](/Physical_property) or [chemical properties](/Chemical_property). Examples include [gas chromatography](/Gas_chromatography) and [liquid chromatography](/Liquid_chromatography). It's how we untangle chemical messes.

chromometer
See [colorimeter](/Colorimeter_(chemistry)).

[cis–trans isomerism](/Cis%E2%trans_isomerism)
A specific type of [stereoisomerism](/Stereoisomerism), also known as geometric isomerism, that arises in [molecules](/Molecule) where there is restricted rotation around a [chemical bond](/Chemical_bond) (most commonly a [double bond](/Double_bond) or within a [ring structure](/Ring_system)). It describes the different spatial arrangements of [substituents](/Substituent) relative to each other on either side of this restricted bond. *Cis* isomers have substituents on the same side, while *trans* isomers have them on opposite sides. This seemingly minor difference can lead to vastly different [physical](/Physical_property) and [chemical properties](/Chemical_property).

[closed system](/Closed_system)
A [thermodynamic system](/Thermodynamic_system) that can exchange [energy](/Energy) (e.g., [heat](/Heat) and [work](/Work_(thermodynamics))) with its surroundings but *cannot* exchange [matter](/Matter). Its mass remains constant. It's a useful idealization for studying energy transformations without the added complication of mass transfer.

[cluster](/Cluster_chemistry)
In [chemistry](/Chemistry), a [cluster](/Cluster) refers to a group of two or more [atoms](/Atom) or [molecules](/Molecule) that are bound together, often by [intermolecular forces](/Intermolecular_force) or [covalent bonds](/Covalent_bond), forming a discrete entity with properties intermediate between those of individual atoms/molecules and bulk matter. [Metal clusters](/Metal_cluster), for instance, are important in [catalysis](/Catalyst).

[cohesion](/Cohesion_(chemistry))
The intrinsic tendency of *similar* [particles](/Particle) or [surfaces](/Surface_science) to cling to one another. This attractive force is a direct result of [intermolecular forces](/Intermolecular_force) acting between identical substances. It is, quite simply, the opposite of [adhesion](/Adhesion).

[colligative property](/Colligative_property)
Any [property](/Physical_property) of a [solution](/Solution_(chemistry)) that depends *solely* upon the ratio of the number of [solute particles](/Solute) to the number of [solvent particles](/Solvent) within that solution, and *not* on the specific chemical nature of the species present. Examples, which demonstrate this rather elegant universality, include [osmotic pressure](/Osmotic_pressure), [freezing-point depression](/Freezing-point_depression), and [boiling-point elevation](/Boiling-point_elevation). They're a testament to the power of counting, rather than identifying.

[colloid](/Colloid)
A [mixture](/Mixture) in which microscopic, insoluble [particles](/Particle) are stably suspended within and evenly dispersed throughout another [substance](/Chemical_substance). This other substance is typically a [liquid](/Liquid), but the term also encompasses [aerosols](/Aerosol) (solids/liquids in a gas) and [gels](/Gel) (solids in a liquid). Thus, a colloid inherently comprises a dispersed phase and a continuous phase. Many [milks](/Milk) are classic examples of colloids, demonstrating their commonality in everyday life.

color standard
A meticulously prepared [liquid solution](/Liquid_solution) of precisely known [chemical composition](/Chemical_composition) and [concentration](/Concentration), and consequently, of a known and standardized [color](/Color). This standard is utilized as a reference point in the [optical analysis](/Optical_analysis) of [samples](/Sample_(material)) of unknown strength. It provides a baseline for comparison, assuming your eyes are calibrated. [4]

color test
A [quantitative analysis](/Quantitative_analysis) of a [substance](/Chemical_substance) performed by comparing the intensity of the [color](/Color) produced when that substance is exposed to a [reagent](/Reagent) with a standard color. This standard color is, naturally, produced similarly in a [solution](/Solution_(chemistry)) of known strength. It's a visual, albeit sometimes subjective, method of quantification. [4]

[colorimeter](/Colorimeter_(chemistry))
Also known as a *chromometer*. Any instrument specifically designed and employed for the [measurement of color](/Colorimetry) based on [optical comparison](/Optical_comparison) with established [standard colors](/Color_standard). [2] More specifically in [chemistry](/Chemistry), it's a device used in [colorimetry](/Colorimetry) that measures the [absorbance](/Absorbance) of specific [wavelengths of light](/Wavelength) by a given [solution](/Solution_(chemistry)). This measurement allows for the determination of the [concentration](/Concentration) of a known [solute](/Solute) in the solution, by applying the principle that solute concentration is directly proportional to absorbance (the [Beer–Lambert law](/Beer%E2%80%93Lambert_law)).

[combustion](/Combustion)
An [exothermic reaction](/Exothermic_reaction) (one that releases [heat](/Heat)) occurring rapidly between an [oxidant](/Oxidizing_agent) (typically [oxygen](/Oxygen)) and a [fuel](/Fuel). This reaction produces substantial amounts of heat and, quite often, visible [light](/Light). It's a vigorous process, often associated with flames and rapid energy release.

An example of large-scale, rapid [combustion](/Combustion).
[Commission on Isotopic Abundances and Atomic Weights](/Commission_on_Isotopic_Abundances_and_Atomic_Weights) (CIAAW)
A rather important, though obscure, international scientific body responsible for periodically reviewing and recommending standard [atomic weights](/Relative_atomic_mass) and [isotopic abundances](/Isotopic_abundance) of the [elements](/Chemical_element). They ensure that the fundamental data chemists rely on is accurate and up-to-date.

[complex](/Complex_(chemistry))
A [molecular entity](/Molecular_entity) that forms through a rather loose association between two or more component molecular entities, which can be either [ionic](/Ion) or uncharged. The corresponding [chemical species](/Chemical_species) also fall under this umbrella. The [bonding](/Chemical_bond) between these components is typically weaker than a full [covalent bond](/Covalent_bond). [2] See also [coordination complex](/Coordination_complex) for a more specific type.

[compound](/Chemical_compound)
A [substance](/Chemical_substance) that is meticulously formed from two or more distinct [chemical elements](/Chemical_element) that are [chemically bonded](/Chemical_bond) together in a fixed [stoichiometric ratio](/Stoichiometry). Unlike a [mixture](/Mixture), a compound has properties entirely different from its constituent elements. [Water](/Water_(molecule)) (H2O) is a compound, not just a mixture of hydrogen and oxygen.

Compton rule
An [empirical law](/Empirical_law) of [physical chemistry](/Physical_chemistry) which rather curiously states that the [heat of fusion](/Enthalpy_of_fusion) of a given [element](/Chemical_element), when multiplied by its [atomic weight](/Relative_atomic_mass) and then divided by its [melting point](/Melting_point) in [kelvin](/Kelvin), consistently approximates a value of 2. It’s an interesting, if niche, observation about the relationship between these properties. [4]

[concatemer](/Concatemer)
A long continuous [molecule](/Molecule) that contains multiple copies of the same [DNA](/DNA) or [RNA](/RNA) sequence linked in series. More broadly, it can refer to any [polymer](/Polymer) composed of multiple identical [monomer](/Monomer) units linked end-to-end.

[concentration](/Concentration)
The precise quantity or [abundance](/Abundance_(chemistry)) of a particular [constituent](/Constituent) within a [mixture](/Mixture), expressed per unit quantity of that mixture. For instance, the amount, in [moles](/Mole_(unit)), of a dissolved [solute](/Solute) per unit [volume](/Volume) of a [solution](/Solution_(chemistry)) is a common measure known as [molar concentration](/Molar_concentration) or [molarity](/Molar_concentration). Various definitions of concentration are employed in [chemistry](/Chemistry), including [mass concentration](/Mass_concentration_(chemistry)) and [volume concentration](/Volume_concentration). Choose your poison, but be precise.

[condensation](/Condensation)
The [phase transition](/Phase_transition) of a [substance](/Chemical_substance) from a [gas](/Gas) to a [liquid](/Liquid). It's the reverse of [vaporization](/Vaporization), often occurring when a gas is cooled or compressed. Think of dew forming on grass.

[condosity](/Condosity)
A rather specialized comparative measurement of the [electrical conductivity](/Electrical_conductivity) of a [solution](/Solution_(chemistry)). It is defined as the [molar concentration](/Molar_concentration) of a [sodium chloride](/Sodium_chloride) (NaCl) solution that exhibits the *same specific electrical conductance* as the solution under examination. It is typically quantified in units of [moles per litre](/Molar_concentration) (or per some other unit of volume). It's a way to standardize conductivity measurements.

[conduction](/Thermal_conduction)
The process of [heat transfer](/Heat_transfer) (or [electrical charge](/Electric_charge) transfer) through direct contact between particles, without any net movement of the [material](/Material) itself. In [thermal conduction](/Thermal_conduction), [kinetic energy](/Kinetic_energy) is passed from more energetic particles to less energetic ones. In [electrical conduction](/Electrical_conductivity), [electrons](/Electron) move through the material.

conductivity
See [electrical conductivity](/Electrical_conductivity) and [thermal conductivity](/Thermal_conductivity). Because specifying which type of conductivity is crucial.

[conductor](/Electrical_conductor)
Any [object](/Object_(philosophy)) or [material](/Material) that readily permits the flow of an [electric current](/Electric_current) in one or more directions. These materials typically have [delocalized electrons](/Delocalized_electron) that can move freely. The opposite, naturally, is an [insulator](/Insulator_(electrical)).

[conformation](/Conformation_(chemistry))
The specific spatial arrangement of [atoms](/Atom) within a [molecule](/Molecule) that allows for distinction between [stereoisomers](/Stereoisomer) which can be interconverted *solely* by rotations around formally [single bonds](/Multiple_bond). These are not different molecules, but different shapes of the same molecule, interconverting rapidly at room temperature. [Chairs](/Chair_conformation) and [boats](/Boat_conformation) in [cyclohexane](/Cyclohexane) are classic examples.

[conjugate acid](/Conjugate_acid)
In a [Brønsted–Lowry acid–base reaction](/Br%C3%B8nsted%E2%80%93Lowry_acid%E2%80%93base_theory), the [species](/Chemical_species) formed when a [base](/Base_(chemistry)) accepts a [proton](/Proton). It's essentially the base with an extra proton.

[conjugate base](/Conjugate_base)
In a [Brønsted–Lowry acid–base reaction](/Br%C3%B8nsted%E2%80%93Lowry_acid%E2%80%93base_theory), the [species](/Chemical_species) formed when an [acid](/Acid) donates a [proton](/Proton). It's essentially the acid minus a proton.

[conjugated system](/Conjugated_system)
A [molecule](/Molecule) that contains [double](/Double_bond) or [triple bonds](/Triple_bond) that are separated by *one* [single bond](/Multiple_bond). For instance, the compound [buta-1,3-diene](/Buta-1,3-diene), with the [chemical structure](/Chemical_structure) H2C=CH−CH=CH2, exemplifies conjugated double bonds. In such molecules, there is a degree of [delocalization of electrons](/Delocalized_electron) within the [pi orbitals](/Pi_orbital) that extends across the carbon atoms linked by the single bond. This delocalization imparts enhanced [stability](/Chemical_stability) and unique [spectroscopic properties](/Spectroscopy). [3]

constitutional isomer
See [structural isomer](/Structural_isomer).

constitutional unit
An [atom](/Atom) or a group of atoms (including any [pendant atoms](/Pendant_group) or groups, should they be present) that collectively comprise a repeating part of the structure of a [macromolecule](/Macromolecule), [oligomer](/Oligomer), [polymer](/Polymer), [block copolymer](/Block_copolymer), or [chain](/Polymer_chain). It's the fundamental repeating module from which larger structures are built. [2]

[convection](/Convection)
A mechanism of [heat transfer](/Heat_transfer) (or [mass transfer](/Mass_transfer)) that occurs through the movement of [fluids](/Fluid) (liquids or gases). In convection, warmer, less dense fluid rises, while cooler, denser fluid sinks, creating a circulation current that transfers heat or mass.

[cooling curve](/Cooling_curve)
A graphical representation, typically a [line graph](/Line_graph), that illustrates the change between different [phases of matter](/Phase_(matter)), commonly from a [gas](/Gas) to a [solid](/Solid) or a [liquid](/Liquid) to a solid, as a function of [time](/Time) and [temperature](/Temperature). For example, it can show how the temperature of a liquid substance decreases over time as it [condenses](/Condensation) and eventually freezes below its [freezing point](/Freezing_point). Plateaus on the curve indicate [phase transitions](/Phase_transition).

coordinate chemistry
A rather vague term. Presumably, this refers to [coordination chemistry](/Coordination_chemistry), the study of [coordination complexes](/Coordination_complex). Precision, please.

coordinate covalent bond
See [dipolar bond](/Dipolar_bond).

[coordination complex](/Coordination_complex)
A [chemical compound](/Chemical_compound) distinguished by a central [atom](/Atom) or [ion](/Ion), which is typically [metallic](/Metal) and referred to as the *coordination center*. This central entity is [bonded](/Chemical_bond) to a surrounding array of other groups of atoms, such as [molecules](/Molecule) or [ions](/Ion), which are known as [ligands](/Ligand) or *complexing agents*. Many [metal-containing compounds](/Metal_compound), particularly those involving [transition metals](/Transition_metal), fall under this category of coordination complexes. They are ubiquitous in [biology](/Biology), [catalysis](/Catalyst), and materials science. See also [complex](/Complex_(chemistry)).

[corrosion](/Corrosion)
An irreversible [interfacial chemical reaction](/Interface_(matter)) of a [material](/Material), most notably a [metal](/Metal), with its surrounding [environment](/Environment). This destructive process results in either the consumption of the material itself or its dissolution into an external component of the environment. It's the slow, inevitable decay of matter, a rather depressing but unavoidable reality.

[coulomb](/Coulomb) (C)
The [SI unit](/International_System_of_Units) of [electric charge](/Electric_charge). It is precisely defined as the amount of charge transported by a constant [electric current](/Electric_current) of one [ampere](/Ampere) flowing for one [second](/Second). It's a fundamental unit for quantifying electrical phenomena.

[counterion](/Counterion)
The [ion](/Ion) that serves as the necessary counterpart to an oppositely charged ion within a [dissociated ionic species](/Ionic_compound). Essentially, it's the [cation](/Cation) that pairs with a given [anion](/Anion), or vice versa, ensuring overall [charge neutrality](/Charge_neutrality). For instance, Na+
is the counterion to Cl−
, and vice versa, in [solutions of sodium chloride](/Sodium_chloride) (NaCl). It's the balancing act of charged particles.

[covalent bond](/Covalent_bond)
Also known as a *molecular bond*. This is a type of [chemical bond](/Chemical_bond) that involves the mutual sharing of [electron pairs](/Electron_pair) between [atoms](/Atom). The stable balance of attractive and repulsive [forces](/Force) that arises between atoms when they engage in this sharing of electrons is precisely what constitutes [covalent bonding](/Covalent_bonding). It's a strong, directional bond, the workhorse of [organic chemistry](/Organic_chemistry).

A [diatomic hydrogen molecule](/Diatomic_molecule), H2
(right), is formed by a [covalent bond](/Covalent_bond) when two single [hydrogen atoms](/Hydrogen) share two [electrons](/Electron) between them.
[critical point](/Critical_point_(thermodynamics))
The definitive end point of a [phase equilibrium curve](/Phase_diagram) or a [pressure-temperature curve](/Phase_diagram). At this specific set of conditions, the distinctions between different [phases](/Phase_(matter)) of a [substance](/Chemical_substance), such as its [liquid](/Liquid) and [vapor](/Vapor) forms, vanish, and they can coexist indistinguishably. The critical point is precisely defined by the intersection of a [critical temperature](/Critical_temperature) (Tc) and a [critical pressure](/Critical_pressure) (pc); above these values, all distinction between phases disappears, and the substance transforms into a [supercritical fluid](/Supercritical_fluid), possessing properties of both a liquid and a gas.

[crucible](/Crucible)
A specialized [ceramic](/Ceramic) or [metal dish](/Metal) or other vessel, designed to withstand extremely high [temperatures](/Temperature). Its purpose is to allow [substances](/Chemical_substance) to be melted, [calcined](/Calcination), or otherwise subjected to intense heat without degrading the container itself. Essential for [pyrochemistry](/Pyrochemistry). [3]

[crystal](/Crystal)
A [solid](/Solid) material whose constituent [particles](/Particle) (such as [atoms](/Atom), [ions](/Ion), or [molecules](/Molecule)) are arranged in an exceptionally orderly, [periodic microscopic structure](/Crystal_structure). This arrangement forms a repeating [lattice](/Crystal_structure) with a definite [geometry](/Geometry) that extends throughout all directions. Such materials are, unsurprisingly, described as *crystalline*. Their ordered structure gives rise to many unique [physical properties](/Physical_property).

[crystallization](/Crystallization)
The [physical process](/Physical_process) by which a [solid](/Solid) forms, where the [atoms](/Atom) or [molecules](/Molecule) are highly organized into a repeating, three-dimensional [crystal lattice](/Crystal_structure). It can occur from a [solution](/Solution_(chemistry)), a [melt](/Melting), or even directly from a [gas](/Gas) (deposition). It's the ultimate act of molecular self-assembly, assuming conditions are favorable.

crystallization point
See [freezing point](/Freezing_point).

[crystallography](/Crystallography)
The branch of [chemistry](/Chemistry) and [physics](/Physics) specifically concerned with the meticulous study of [crystalline solids](/Crystal). This includes the precise determination of their internal [structure](/Crystal_structure) (e.g., using [X-ray diffraction](/X-ray_scattering_techniques)) and the comprehensive understanding of their resulting [properties](/Physical_property).

[cuvette](/Cuvette)
A small, transparent container, typically rectangular, used in [spectroscopy](/Spectroscopy) experiments. Usually constructed from [plastic](/Plastic), [glass](/Glass), or [quartz](/Quartz), it is specifically designed to hold a [sample](/Sample_(material)) (most commonly a [liquid](/Liquid)) for measurement inside a [spectrometer](/Spectrometer). Cuvettes must be impeccably clean and as optically transparent as possible to minimize any interference with the [beams of light](/Light_beam) upon which [spectroscopic techniques](/Spectroscopy) rely. Their purity directly impacts measurement accuracy.

[cyclic](/Cyclic_compound)
(Of a [molecule](/Molecule)) Containing one or more [ring structures](/Ring_system) formed by the bonding of [atoms](/Atom). This contrasts with [acyclic](/Open-chain_compound) compounds, and the presence of rings often imparts unique [stereochemical](/Stereochemistry) and [reactivity](/Reactivity_(chemistry)) properties.

