D

[dalton](/Dalton_(unit)) (Da)
Also known as the *unified atomic mass unit* (u). This is a unit of [mass](/Mass) defined with remarkable precision as exactly 1/12 of the mass of a free, unexcited [atom](/Atom) of [carbon-12](/Carbon-12) at rest. It is, rather conveniently, approximately equal to the mass of one [nucleon](/Nucleon) ([proton](/Proton) or [neutron](/Neutron)). It is the standard unit for expressing [atomic](/Atomic_mass) and [molecular masses](/Molecular_weight).

[Dalton's law of partial pressures](/Dalton%27s_law)
An [empirical law](/Empirical_law) concerning [gases](/Gas) which states that, in a [mixture of non-reacting gases](/Gas_mixture), the total [pressure](/Pressure) exerted by all of the combined gases is precisely equal to the sum of the [partial pressures](/Partial_pressure) exerted by each individual gas. It’s a simple additive principle for gas mixtures, assuming they behave themselves.

[d-block](/D-block)
The colloquial name given to the section of the [periodic table](/Periodic_table_of_the_elements) that encompasses [Groups](/Group_(periodic_table)) 3 through 12. The [elements](/Chemical_element) residing here are known as the [transition metals](/Transition_metal), characterized by their [d-orbitals](/D_orbital) being partially filled with [electrons](/Electron). They exhibit variable [oxidation states](/Oxidation_state) and often form colorful [coordination complexes](/Coordination_complex).

dative bond
See [dipolar bond](/Dipolar_bond).

[debye](/Debye) (D)
A non-[SI unit](/International_System_of_Units) of measurement specifically for [electric dipole moment](/Electric_dipole_moment), defined as 10−18 statcoulomb-centimetres. While not SI, it's widely used in [chemistry](/Chemistry) and [atomic physics](/Atomic_physics) due to its convenient scale for molecular dipoles. See also [electric dipole moment](/Electric_dipole_moment).

[deionization](/DI_water)
The process of removing [ions](/Ion) from a [solution](/Solution_(chemistry)) by any suitable method. In the context of [water](/Water_(molecule)), this typically refers to the removal of mineral ions such as [sodium](/Sodium), [iron](/Iron), and [calcium](/Calcium), resulting in "deionized water" (DI water), which is less conductive.

[deliquescence](/Deliquescence)
A [substance's](/Chemical_substance) inherent [affinity for water](/Hygroscopy), often characterized by its pronounced tendency to absorb [moisture](/Moisture) directly from the [atmosphere](/Atmosphere_of_Earth) to the point where it forms an [aqueous solution](/Aqueous_solution). Most strongly deliquescent substances are [salts](/Salt_(chemistry)), such as [calcium chloride](/Calcium_chloride) and [potassium carbonate](/Potassium_carbonate). They essentially dissolve themselves in the air’s humidity.

[delocalized electron](/Delocalized_electron)
Any [electron](/Electron) within a [molecule](/Molecule), [ion](/Ion), or [solid metal](/Solid_solution) that is *not* exclusively associated with an individual [atom](/Atom) or a single [covalent bond](/Covalent_bond). This term can refer to electrons involved in [resonance](/Resonance_(chemistry)) within [conjugated systems](/Conjugated_system) or [aromatic compounds](/Aromatic_compound); to [free electrons](/Free_electron_model) that enable [electrical conductivity](/Electrical_conductivity) in [metals](/Metal); or to electrons residing within [delocalized molecular orbitals](/Molecular_orbital) that span multiple adjacent atoms. They are, in essence, shared by many.

[density](/Density)
An [intensive property](/Intensive_and_extensive_properties) of a [substance](/Chemical_substance), defined as its [mass](/Mass) per unit [volume](/Volume). It is elegantly expressed by the equation d = m/V. It tells you how much "stuff" is packed into a given space.

[denticity](/Denticity)
A specific measure in [coordination chemistry](/Coordination_chemistry) that quantifies the number of [donor groups](/Donor_atom) within a single [ligand](/Ligand) that are simultaneously [bonded](/Chemical_bond) to a central [atom](/Atom) (typically a [metal ion](/Metal_ion)) in a [coordination complex](/Coordination_complex). A [monodentate ligand](/Monodentate_ligand) has one donor group, a [bidentate ligand](/Bidentate_ligand) has two, and so on.

[deposition](/Deposition_(chemistry))
The process by which [particles](/Particle) (typically solid) settle out from within a [solution](/Solution_(chemistry)) or [mixture](/Mixture). More broadly, in [phase transitions](/Phase_transition), it refers to the direct change of a [substance](/Chemical_substance) from a [gas](/Gas) to a [solid](/Solid) without passing through a [liquid](/Liquid) phase (reverse of [sublimation](/Sublimation_(chemistry))).

depression of freezing point
See [freezing-point depression](/Freezing-point_depression).

[desiccant](/Desiccant)
Also known as a *drying agent*. This is a [hygroscopic substance](/Hygroscopy) employed to induce or maintain a state of dryness or [desiccation](/Desiccation) (i.e., the absence of [moisture](/Moisture)) in its immediate vicinity. It achieves this by abstracting [water molecules](/Water_(molecule)) from other substances. Desiccants manifest in a variety of forms and operate via diverse principles, ranging from simple [absorption](/Absorption_(chemistry)) to the direct [chemical bonding](/Chemical_bond) of water molecules. They are the silent guardians against unwanted humidity.

[desiccation](/Desiccation)
The process of extreme drying, or the complete removal of [moisture](/Moisture) from a [substance](/Chemical_substance). Often achieved using a [desiccant](/Desiccant) or through methods like [freeze-drying](/Lyophilization).

[deuterium](/Deuterium)
Also known as *hydrogen-2* or *heavy hydrogen*, and symbolized as 2H or D. It is one of the two stable [isotopes](/Isotope) of a [hydrogen atom](/Hydrogen), distinguished by its [nucleus](/Atomic_nucleus) containing one [proton](/Proton) and one [neutron](/Neutron). Deuterium is both noticeably heavier and considerably less abundant in nature than its more common counterpart, [protium](/Protium) (1H). Its presence can significantly alter reaction rates (kinetic isotope effect).

[deuteron](/Deuteron)
The [nucleus](/Atomic_nucleus) of a [deuterium](/Deuterium) [atom](/Atom) (an [isotope of hydrogen](/Isotope)), containing precisely one [proton](/Proton) and one [neutron](/Neutron). It's the core of heavy hydrogen.

Dewar flask
See [vacuum flask](/Vacuum_flask).

[dianion](/Dianion)
A [compound](/Chemical_compound) or [molecular entity](/Molecular_entity) that bears precisely two negative [electric charges](/Electric_charge). These charges may be localized on a single [atom](/Atom), distributed across different atoms, or even [delocalized](/Delocalized_electron) across a larger structure. [2]

[diastereomer](/Diastereomer)
A type of [stereoisomer](/Stereoisomer) that is not a [mirror image](/Mirror_image) of another stereoisomer. Diastereomers have the same [chemical formula](/Chemical_formula) and [connectivity](/Chemical_connectivity) but differ in the spatial arrangement of their atoms and are not [enantiomers](/Enantiomer). They have different [physical](/Physical_property) and [chemical properties](/Chemical_property).

[diatomic](/Diatomic)
Composed of exactly two [atoms](/Atom), which may be of the same or different [elements](/Chemical_element). [Oxygen](/Oxygen) (O2) and [carbon monoxide](/Carbon_monoxide) (CO) are examples. Contrast [monatomic](/Monatomic) and [polyatomic](/Polyatomic).

[diatomic molecule](/Diatomic_molecule)
Any [molecule](/Molecule) that consists of only two [atoms](/Atom), regardless of whether those atoms are of the same [element](/Chemical_element) (e.g., O2, N2) or different elements (e.g., HCl, CO).

[diffusion](/Diffusion)
The spontaneous net movement of [atoms](/Atom) or [molecules](/Molecule) from a region of higher [concentration](/Concentration) to a region of lower concentration. This process is driven by a [gradient](/Gradient) in the [chemical potential](/Chemical_potential) of the diffusing [species](/Chemical_species) and fundamentally relies on the [random walk](/Random_walk) of particles. Consequently, it results in the mixing or [mass transport](/Mass_transfer) of substances without requiring any directed bulk motion. It's how things spread out.

[dilatant](/Dilatant)
(Of a [substance](/Chemical_substance)) Possessing the rather counter-intuitive ability to *increase* in [volume](/Volume) when its shape is forcibly changed. These are sometimes called shear-thickening fluids. [4]

dilution
The process of reducing the [concentration](/Concentration) of a [solute](/Solute) in a [solution](/Solution_(chemistry)) by adding more [solvent](/Solvent). It's a common laboratory procedure for preparing solutions of desired concentrations.

[dimer](/Dimer_(chemistry))
An [oligomer](/Oligomer) consisting of precisely two [monomers](/Monomer) that are joined together by [chemical bonds](/Chemical_bond). These bonds can be quite variable in strength (strong or weak) and nature (covalent or [intermolecular](/Intermolecular_force)). A [homodimer](/Homodimer) is composed of two identical molecules, while a [heterodimer](/Heterodimer) consists of two different molecules.

[dipolar bond](/Dipolar_bond)
Also known as a *coordinate covalent bond*, *coordinate bond*, *dative bond*, and *semipolar bond*. This is a specific type of [covalent bond](/Covalent_bond) formed through the [coordination](/Coordination_chemistry) of two or more electrically neutral [moieties](/Moiety_(chemistry)). The combination results in a [charge-separated molecule](/Zwitterion) or [coordination complex](/Coordination_complex), where two [electrons](/Electron) originating *from the same atom* are shared between the [donor atom](/Donor_atom) and an [acceptor atom](/Acceptor_atom), thereby creating an internal, two-center [molecular dipole moment](/Molecular_dipole_moment). [2]

[dipole](/Dipole)
The electric or magnetic separation of [electric charge](/Electric_charge) into a pair of charges that possess equal magnitude but opposite sign (one positively charged, one negatively charged), separated by some typically small distance. It's a fundamental concept in understanding [molecular polarity](/Chemical_polarity).

dipole moment
A general term. See [electric dipole moment](/Electric_dipole_moment), [magnetic dipole moment](/Magnetic_dipole_moment), [molecular dipole moment](/Molecular_dipole_moment), [bond dipole moment](/Bond_dipole_moment), [electron electric dipole moment](/Electron_electric_dipole_moment), [electron magnetic dipole moment](/Electron_magnetic_dipole_moment), and [nuclear magnetic moment](/Nuclear_magnetic_moment). Be specific, please.

[dispersion](/Dispersion_(chemistry))
A [system](/Physical_system) in which [particles](/Particle) of one [material](/Material) are distributed throughout a continuous [phase](/Phase_(matter)) of another material. The two phases may exist in the same or different [states of matter](/State_of_matter). Dispersions where the particles are sufficiently large to undergo [sedimentation](/Sedimentation) are termed [suspensions](/Suspension_(chemistry)), while those with smaller particles are classified as [colloids](/Colloid) or, in the case of true molecular-level mixing, [solutions](/Solution_(chemistry)).

[dissociation](/Dissociation_(chemistry))
Any [process](/Physical_process) by which a [polyatomic molecule](/Polyatomic_molecule) or [molecular entity](/Molecular_entity) (e.g., an [ionic compound](/Ionic_compound) or [coordination complex](/Coordination_complex)), or an aggregate of molecular entities, separates or splits into two or more smaller [molecules](/Molecule), [atoms](/Atom), [ions](/Ion), [radicals](/Radical_(chemistry)), or other constituent parts. This process is usually, though not always, [reversible](/Reversible_reaction). Common examples include [unimolecular heterolysis](/Heterolysis) and [homolysis](/Homolysis), the [dissolution of salts](/Solvation), and [acid dissociation](/Acid_dissociation_constant). It's the act of breaking apart. Contrast [association](/Association_(chemistry)).

[dissolution](/Solvation)
Also known as *solvation*. This is the intimate interaction of a [solvent](/Solvent) with the [molecules](/Molecule) or [ions](/Ion) of a [solute](/Solute). This interaction involves various forces, including [bond formation](/Chemical_bond), [hydrogen bonding](/Hydrogen_bond), and [van der Waals forces](/Van_der_Waals_force). It's the process by which a solute disperses evenly throughout a solvent to form a [solution](/Solution_(chemistry)).

A [sodium ion](/Sodium_ion) (Na+
) forms a [solvation complex](/Solvation_shell) with [water molecules](/Water_(molecule)) when dissolved in an [aqueous solution](/Aqueous_solution).
[distillation](/Distillation)
A fundamental [separation process](/Separation_process) employed to isolate the component [substances](/Chemical_substance) of a [liquid mixture](/Liquid_mixture). It cleverly exploits differences in the [relative volatility](/Volatility_(chemistry)) of the mixture's components through a sequence of selective [boiling](/Boiling) and subsequent [condensation](/Condensation). The apparatus specifically used to distill a substance is called a *still*, and the re-condensed substance yielded by the process is, rather predictably, called the *distillate*.

[double bond](/Double_bond)
A type of [covalent bond](/Covalent_bond) that involves the sharing of *two* [pairs of electrons](/Electron_pair) between two [atoms](/Atom). This makes it stronger and shorter than a [single bond](/Multiple_bond) but also more reactive, due to the presence of a [pi bond](/Pi_bond).

[double decomposition](/Double_decomposition)
An older, less precise term for a [double displacement reaction](/Salt_metathesis_reaction), also known as a [metathesis reaction](/Metathesis). It implies that both [reactants](/Reactant) "decompose" and exchange parts.

[double displacement](/Salt_metathesis_reaction)
Also known as a [salt metathesis reaction](/Salt_metathesis_reaction). A type of [chemical reaction](/Chemical_reaction) in which the [cations](/Cation) and [anions](/Anion) of two different [ionic compounds](/Ionic_compound) switch partners, forming two new compounds. This often leads to the formation of a [precipitate](/Precipitate), a [gas](/Gas), or [water](/Water_(molecule)).

[double salt](/Double_salt)
1.&#160;&#160;A [salt](/Salt_(chemistry)) that is composed of more than one distinct [cation](/Cation) or [anion](/Anion), or one which, upon [hydrolysis](/Hydrolysis), yields two different cations and anions.
2.&#160;&#160;Alternatively, it can refer to a salt that is a [molecular combination](/Molecular_combination) of two other salts, forming a single [crystalline structure](/Crystal_structure) with distinct properties. [4]

double-replacement reaction
See [double displacement](/Salt_metathesis_reaction).

[dropping point](/Dropping_point)
A specific [temperature](/Temperature) at which a [grease](/Grease) undergoes a [phase transition](/Phase_transition) from a semi-solid to a [liquid](/Liquid) state under standardized conditions. [4] It represents the upper limit at which the grease retains its structural integrity, though it doesn't necessarily indicate the maximum temperature at which it can still be effectively used. It's a critical parameter for lubricant selection.

[dry box](/Dry_box)
A specialized, sealed chamber or container meticulously designed to maintain an interior environment of extremely low [humidity](/Humidity). This is often achieved by continuously flushing it with an [inert gas](/Inert_gas) like [argon](/Argon) or with air rigorously scrubbed of [carbon dioxide](/Carbon_dioxide) and [water vapor](/Water_vapor). Its purpose is to provide an [inert atmosphere](/Inert_atmosphere) where highly [reactive chemicals](/Reactive_chemical) or [moisture-sensitive procedures](/Moisture_sensitivity) can be safely manipulated in the [laboratory](/Laboratory). Essential for handling pyrophoric or hygroscopic substances. [4]

drying agent
See [desiccant](/Desiccant).

[ductility](/Ductility)
Also known as *malleability*. This is a crucial measure of a [material's](/Material) inherent ability to undergo significant [plastic deformation](/Plastic_deformation) (i.e., change shape permanently) *before* ultimately rupturing. It is typically expressed as a percentage of elongation or percentage of area reduction observed in a [tensile test](/Tensile_testing) and is popularly characterized by the material's capacity to be stretched into a thin [wire](/Wire). [Metals](/Metal) like [copper](/Copper) and [gold](/Gold) are excellent examples.

dystectic mixture
A rather specific [mixture](/Mixture) of two or more [substances](/Chemical_substance) which, rather remarkably, possesses the *highest* [melting point](/Melting_point) of all possible mixtures of those particular substances. It’s the peak of the melting point curve. [4] Contrast [eutectic mixture](/Eutectic_mixture).

