E

earth metal
See [alkaline earth metal](/Alkaline_earth_metal). A rather imprecise term.

ebullition
See [boiling](/Boiling).

effective molecular diameter
The conceptual physical extent of the [electron cloud](/Electron_cloud) enveloping a [molecule](/Molecule) of a particular [gas](/Gas). This value is calculated through various methods and is usually expressed in [nanometres](/Nanometre) or [ångströms](/Ångstr%C3%B6m). It's a way to estimate how much space a molecule effectively occupies, which is important for gas kinetics. [4]

[effervescence](/Effervescence)
The spontaneous escape of [gas](/Gas) from an [aqueous solution](/Aqueous_solution) *without* the application of external [heat](/Heat). This process is accompanied by characteristic bubbling, foaming, or fizzing. A common example is the release of [carbon dioxide](/Carbon_dioxide) from [carbonated water](/Carbonated_water). It's a visual indicator of a gas coming out of solution.

[electric charge](/Electric_charge)
A fundamental, intrinsic property of [matter](/Matter), measured in [coulombs](/Coulomb), that dictates how a [particle](/Particle) will experience and generate [electromagnetic interaction](/Electromagnetic_interaction). It can be positive or negative, and like charges repel, while opposite charges attract. It's the basis of all electrical phenomena.

[electric dipole moment](/Electric_dipole_moment)
A quantitative measure of the separation of positive and negative [electric charges](/Electric_charge) within an electrical system. Essentially, it quantifies the system's overall [electrical polarity](/Electrical_polarity). The [SI unit](/International_System_of_Units) for measuring electric dipole moment is the [coulomb-metre](/Coulomb) (C⋅m), but the [debye](/Debye) (D), a non-SI unit, is also widely used in [chemistry](/Chemistry) and [atomic physics](/Atomic_physics) due to its convenient scale for molecular dipoles. It tells you how unevenly charge is distributed.

[electrical conductivity](/Electrical_conductivity)
The measure of a [material's](/Material) ability to conduct an [electric current](/Electric_current). Materials with high electrical conductivity (e.g., [metals](/Metal)) allow charge to flow easily, while those with low conductivity ([insulators](/Insulator_(electrical))) resist it. It's the inverse of [electrical resistivity](/Electrical_resistivity).

[electrical resistivity](/Electrical_resistivity)
A fundamental [property](/Physical_property) of a [material](/Material) that quantifies how strongly it resists the flow of [electric current](/Electric_current). It's the inverse of [electrical conductivity](/Electrical_conductivity).

[electricity](/Electricity)
The set of [physical phenomena](/Physical_phenomenon) associated with the presence and flow of [electric charge](/Electric_charge). This includes things like [currents](/Electric_current), [fields](/Electric_field), and [potentials](/Electric_potential). It's a fundamental force of nature, harnessed for myriad purposes.

[electride](/Electride)
A rather unusual [ionic compound](/Ionic_compound) for which the [anion](/Anion) is, remarkably, a mere [electron](/Electron). In these compounds, electrons are trapped within cavities in the [crystal lattice](/Crystal_structure) and act as anionic species. They are highly reactive.

[electrochemical cell](/Electrochemical_cell)
A specialized device capable of performing one of two functions: either generating [electrical energy](/Electrical_energy) from [chemical reactions](/Chemical_reaction) (in which case it is known as a [galvanic](/Galvanic_cell) or [voltaic cell](/Voltaic_cell)), or utilizing electrical energy to *drive* [chemical reactions](/Chemical_reaction) that would otherwise not occur spontaneously (in which case it is known as an [electrolytic cell](/Electrolytic_cell)). For instance, a [battery](/Electrochemical_battery) fundamentally contains one or more galvanic cells, each meticulously constructed from two [electrodes](/Electrode) arranged to facilitate an [oxidation–reduction reaction](/Redox) that produces an [electromotive force](/Electromotive_force).

[electrochemistry](/Electrochemistry)
A distinct branch of [physical chemistry](/Physical_chemistry) that meticulously investigates the intrinsic relationship between [electrical potential](/Electrical_potential) difference and identifiable [chemical change](/Chemical_change). This understanding is achieved either through analyzing the [chemical reactions](/Chemical_reaction) that accompany the passage of an [electric current](/Electric_current) or by studying the [potential difference](/Electric_potential_difference) that arises from a particular chemical reaction. It's where electrons truly show their power.

[electrolyte](/Electrolyte)
A [solution](/Solution_(chemistry)) that possesses the ability to conduct a certain amount of [electric current](/Electric_current). Electrolytes can be broadly categorized into [weak](/Weak_electrolyte) and [strong electrolytes](/Strong_electrolyte), depending on the extent to which their constituent [ions](/Ion) [dissociate](/Dissociation_(chemistry)) in solution. Crucial for [electrochemical cells](/Electrochemical_cell) and biological processes.

[electromagnetic radiation](/Electromagnetic_radiation)
A type of [wave](/Wave) that, unlike sound waves, requires no [medium](/Medium) and can propagate through a [vacuum](/Vacuum) as well as through [material](/Material). It is fundamentally classified as a self-propagating wave, composed of oscillating [electric](/Electric_field) and [magnetic fields](/Magnetic_field). This vast spectrum includes everything from [radio waves](/Radio_wave) to [gamma rays](/Gamma_ray), with [visible light](/Light) being a tiny, familiar portion.

[electromagnetic spectrum](/Electromagnetic_spectrum)
The full range of all possible [frequencies](/Frequency) of [electromagnetic radiation](/Electromagnetic_radiation), extending from very low-frequency [radio waves](/Radio_wave) to extremely high-frequency [gamma rays](/Gamma_ray), and encompassing [microwaves](/Microwave), [infrared](/Infrared), [visible light](/Light), [ultraviolet](/Ultraviolet), and [X-rays](/X-ray) in between. It's a continuous spectrum, a testament to the versatility of light.

[electromagnetism](/Electromagnetism)
The fundamental [physical interaction](/Fundamental_interaction) that occurs between electrically charged [particles](/Particle). It is responsible for all [electric](/Electricity) and [magnetic phenomena](/Magnetism), and it dictates how [particles](/Particle) move and interact due to their [electric charge](/Electric_charge) and electrical properties. It's one of the four fundamental forces of the universe, and arguably the most relevant to chemistry.

[electromotive force](/Electromotive_force) (emf)
The [electrical potential difference](/Electric_potential_difference) generated by an [electrochemical cell](/Electrochemical_cell) or other [energy source](/Energy_source) that drives an [electric current](/Electric_current). It's the "push" that makes electrons flow, measured in [volts](/Volt).

[electron](/Electron)
A fundamental type of [subatomic particle](/Subatomic_particle) that carries an elementary, immutable negative [electric charge](/Electric_charge). Electrons orbit the [nucleus](/Atomic_nucleus) of an [atom](/Atom) in specific [electron shells](/Electron_shell) and are primarily responsible for forming [chemical bonds](/Chemical_bond) and mediating [chemical reactions](/Chemical_reaction). They are the currency of chemistry. Contrast [positron](/Positron).

[electron acceptor](/Electron_acceptor)
A [chemical species](/Chemical_species) that is capable of receiving [electrons](/Electron) from another species in a [redox reaction](/Redox). By accepting electrons, it becomes [reduced](/Reduction_(chemistry)) and acts as an [oxidizing agent](/Oxidizing_agent).

[electron capture](/Electron_capture)
A specific type of [nuclear transformation](/Nuclear_transmutation) whereby the [proton-rich nucleus](/Proton-rich_nucleus) of an electrically neutral [atom](/Atom) absorbs, or "captures," an [electron](/Electron) from one of its own inner [electron shells](/Electron_shell) (frequently those closest to the nucleus). This event triggers a [reaction](/Chemical_reaction) that results in a [nuclear proton](/Proton) being converted into a [neutron](/Neutron), accompanied by the simultaneous emission of an [electron neutrino](/Electron_neutrino). [2]

[electron configuration](/Electron_configuration)
The precise distribution of the [electrons](/Electron) of an [atom](/Atom) or [molecule](/Molecule) within their respective [atomic](/Atomic_orbital) or [molecular orbitals](/Molecular_orbital). An elaborate system of notation is employed to concisely and uniquely represent this information for each [atomic species](/Atomic_species). Knowledge of the specific arrangements of electrons in different atoms is indispensable for comprehending the formation of [chemical bonds](/Chemical_bond) and the underlying organization of the [periodic table of the elements](/Periodic_table_of_the_elements). It's the blueprint for an atom's reactivity.

[electron deficiency](/Electron_deficiency)
A state in a [molecule](/Molecule) or [ion](/Ion) where there are not enough [valence electrons](/Valence_electron) to form a complete [octet](/Octet_rule) around a central [atom](/Atom) or to fully satisfy all bonding requirements. [Electrophiles](/Electrophile) are typically electron deficient.

[electron donor](/Electron_donor)
A [chemical species](/Chemical_species) that is capable of providing [electrons](/Electron) to another species in a [redox reaction](/Redox). By donating electrons, it becomes [oxidized](/Oxidation) and acts as a [reducing agent](/Reducing_agent).

[electron electric dipole moment](/Electron_electric_dipole_moment) (d e)
An intrinsic [property](/Physical_property) of an [electron](/Electron) such that its [potential energy](/Potential_energy) is linearly related to the strength of its [electric field](/Electric_field). It's a measure of the spatial distribution of an electron's negative charge within the electric field it generates. While theoretically predicted to be zero in the [Standard Model](/Standard_Model), experimental searches for a non-zero electron EDM are crucial for probing new [physics](/Physics). See also [electric dipole moment](/Electric_dipole_moment).

[electron magnetic dipole moment](/Electron_magnetic_dipole_moment)
Also known as the *electron magnetic moment*. This refers to the intrinsic [magnetic moment](/Magnetic_moment) of an [electron](/Electron), which arises from the inherent properties of its [spin](/Spin_(physics)) and [electric charge](/Electric_charge). It is approximately equal to &#8722;9.284764×10−24 [joules](/Joule) per [tesla](/Tesla_(unit)). It's why electrons behave like tiny magnets.

[electron neutrino](/Electron_neutrino)
A [lepton](/Lepton), a fundamental [subatomic particle](/Subatomic_particle) with no [electric charge](/Electric_charge) and very little [mass](/Mass), that is produced during certain [radioactive decays](/Radioactive_decay), such as [beta decay](/Beta_decay) and [electron capture](/Electron_capture).

[electron pair](/Electron_pair)
Two [electrons](/Electron) that occupy the same [molecular orbital](/Molecular_orbital) but possess opposite [spins](/Spin_(physics)). Electron pairs are the fundamental units that form [chemical bonds](/Chemical_bond) (as in a [covalent bond](/Covalent_bond)) or exist as [lone pairs](/Lone_pair) of [valence electrons](/Valence_electron). It is also possible, though less common in stable molecules, for electrons to exist individually as [unpaired electrons](/Unpaired_electron) (as in [radicals](/Radical_(chemistry))).

[electron shell](/Electron_shell)
A conceptual [orbital](/Atomic_orbital) or region around the [nucleus](/Atomic_nucleus) of an [atom](/Atom) that contains a fixed number of [electrons](/Electron) (typically two in the innermost shell, and often eight in subsequent shells, as described by the [octet rule](/Octet_rule)). Electrons within the same shell have similar [energy levels](/Energy_level).

[electronegativity](/Electronegativity) (χ)
A crucial [chemical property](/Chemical_property) that quantifies the intrinsic tendency of an [atom](/Atom) within a [molecule](/Molecule) to attract a shared [pair of electrons](/Electron_pair) (or, more broadly, [electron density](/Electron_density)) towards itself. An atom's electronegativity is influenced by both its [nuclear charge](/Nuclear_charge) (which is proportional to the number of [protons](/Proton) in its nucleus) and the number and spatial location of the electrons present in its [atomic shells](/Electron_